<HEADLINE> Feature: Thais Splash Joyous Water as Economy Recovers  by Yuan Li </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- With water flying every way,
Bangkok becomes a battlefield Thursday as Thai people celebrate
the traditional Thai New Year which is also called Songkran or the
Water Festival.
</P>
<P>
Water guns, buckets, big bowls and containers of every
description are used as weapons with water as ammunition.
</P>
<P>
But this is a battlefield without enemies. People splash water
on one another joyfully, no matter where you come from, what you
look like or how old you are. The water is good-natured, believed
to flow and take away all bad omens and the inauspicious, as is
especially the case this year.
</P>
<P>
It has been more than two years during which the Thais had to
bear the hardships of an economic crisis. Now, since the economy
has been recovering, they can relax a bit and heartily celebrate
the festival.
</P>
<P>
"If you'll excuse me, I've got some serious business to do!"
yelled Pisut Khloykhlaew, a 20-some man working for a import and
export company, before joining his friends.
</P>
<P>
Pisut, sopped up to the skin, was "caught" in a convenience
store on the flooded Khaosan Road when putting his mobile phone
into a plastic bag in case it will be damaged by water.
</P>
<P>
"Songkran festival is the day that I look forward most in a
year. I can't miss it. This year I have even more reasons to
celebrate because my company's business is improving," Pisut said.
"Tomorrow I will drive out of Bangkok with my friends to other
provinces to celebrate."
</P>
<P>
The export situation has indeed improved a lot in the country
this year, with the export volume reaching 5.57 billion U.S.
dollars in February, a 32.7-percent increase over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Khaosan Road, a foreign backpacker paradise, always turns out
to be the most exciting place to go in Bangkok during the Songkran
festival, which falls between April 13 and 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
Merrymakers on the road, foreigners and locals alike, "attacked
" one another frantically.
</P>
<P>
Most of them waved the 35-baht (90 U.S. cents) long-barrel
squirt guns which have become the weapon of choice this year.
</P>
<P>
But this seems not crazy enough when compared with water tanks,
some of which are spotted on the street, with people standing on
the top, shooting water down on others with huge pipes.
</P>
<P>
In fact, these water tanks were sent by the Bangkok
Metropolitan Administration to supply the ammunition -- water --
to the revelers.
</P>
<P>
However, Kanmchorn Luangwaranan, the storekeeper of the Inter
Slide photo shop, looks a little bit upset. The business is not as
good as he expected.
</P>
<P>
"As the economy turned around, many Bangkokains went abroad to
spend their holidays. There are fewer people here this year than
last year," he said gloomily.
</P>
<P>
According to Skyline tour company, bookings to foreign
destinations have soared by 20 to 30 percent from last year's
figures.
</P>
<P>
A salesman of Weekend Tours company said, "Trips (during the
Songkran festival) were booked one to two months in advance. Two
to three times more advance bookings were made than in the past."
</P>
<P>
Thailand sank into recession in 1997 after floating its
currency. However, the country has recovered, from a negative 14-
percent growth in 1998 to an expansion of 4.2 percent last year,
and with a barely discernible inflation rate of 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
More impressively, the country's central planning agency, the
National Economic and Social Development Board, announced recently
that this year's economic growth was on course for a further 4.4-
percent rise.
</P>
<P>
"All the economic news is so encouraging and the future so
bright that we can't help but enjoy ourselves," Smith
Patravanichkul, a businessman working for a car export company,
said.
</P>
<P>
Off Khaosan Road, you still have difficulty to avoid getting
drenched. Driving pickups, the country's largest export automobile
unit, many people took pleasure in pouring water on people in any
open place.
</P>
<P>
"They are pouring water of blessing and sharing their happiness
at the country's improved economic situation with everyone," Smith
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
