<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA -- A total of 1,170 refugees from the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC) and the Sudan have entered the Arua
District in the northwestern Uganda from January to March, the New
Vision, a leading newspaper of Uganda, reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the refugees, 59 percent or 596 are male and 574 female.
There were 204 children under five years old while 436 were under
17 and over 530 were adults, the newspaper quoted Arua Refugee
Desk Officer Benny Mike Wafula as saying. (Uganda-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- China pursues a policy of treating all ethnic
minorities as equals and accords minorities with special care, a
Chinese official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 56th session of the United Nations Commission
on Human Rights, Alternate Representative of the Chinese
delegation Li Baodong said that the minorities in China, like the
Han majority, enjoy not only the full range of civil rights
granted by the Chinese Constitution and other laws, but also the
rights legally privileged to them.
</P>
<P>
China is a unified multi-ethnic country, and her 55 ethnic
minority groups make up for 8.98 percent of the total population,
Li told the 53-member commission. All 55 ethnic minority groups,
irrespective of their population size, have their own
representative in the National People's Congress and the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference. (China-Human Rights-
Minorities)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien arrived here
Thursday morning from Cairo accompanied by his wife and a
delegation from the Canadian House of Commons on a two-day
official visit.
</P>
<P>
Chretien was greeted at the airport by his Lebanese counterpart
Salim Hoss with whom he held the first round of talks.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian official will meet Speaker Nabih Berri later
Thursday and President Emile Lahoud Friday morning. Chretien will
also visit the headquarters of "Liban Post" which is run by a
Canadian company. (Lebanon-Canada)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian President K. R. Narayanan is scheduled to
begin his state visit to France on April 16, aimed at enhancing
economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Lalit Mansingh said Thursday that the visit,
first-ever by an Indian head of state to France, would provide "
depth" to bilateral ties after the strategic dialogue initiated
between India and France during Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee's visit to France in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
An investment promotion agreement is expected to be signed
during the visit in a bid to remove obstacles in trading between
the two countries. (India-France-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Belgian King Albert II underwent an emergency heart
operation early Thursday and the quadruple bypass operation turned
out to be successful, according to hospital sources.
</P>
<P>
The operation took two and a half hours in the early morning
after the king was hospitalized on Wednesday night after feeling
chest pains that were diagnosed as having been caused by the
narrowing of the blood vessels in the heart.
</P>
<P>
The operation was conducted by Doctor Hugo van Ermen at
Brussels's Onze Lieve Vrouw d'Alost Hospital. (Belgium-King-
Operation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin met Thursday
with Benita Ferrero-Waldner, head of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), and the two discussed Chechnya
and investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting in the Kremlin, Putin told Ferrero-Waldner
that the OSCE is the main European security system and that OSCE
activities should be strengthened not only in former Soviet
republics but also elsewhere like Kosovo, said Sergei Prikhodko,
deputy head of the Russian presidential staff. (Russia-OSCE-
Meeting) 
</P>
</TEXT>
