<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kyrgyz Lawmaker Rejects U.S. Criticism Over Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-three Kyrgyz lawmakers on
Thursday accused United States observers of not being objective in
assessing the results of the recent parliamentary election in the
Central Asian republic.
</P>
<P>
In an open letter, the lawmakers said the international
missions had made "a non-objective and even negative assessment"
of the elections.
</P>
<P>
The missions had insisted that the election should be held in
compliance with legislation, which had been prepared with the
assistance of experts for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe "to meet high international standards."
</P>
<P>
"That is why it was on the whole staged on the basis of strict
adherence to democratic principles and in accordance with
international norms," the Interfax news agency quoted the letter
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The arrest in late March of Felix Kulov, an opposition leader,
"was not related to his activity aimed at the state's current
leadership," it said.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the arrest "was a logical result of a more-than-two-
year investigation into the criminal and anti-constitutional
activities which he had committed during the years when he
occupied key government positions," the lawmakers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
