<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Solution to Cyprus Issue Reaffirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' National Council, the top
advisory body to President Glafcos Clerides, reaffirmed Friday that
it will continue to seek a federal solution to the Cyprus question.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made at a Council meeting during which Clerides
exchanged views with leaders and representatives of political
parties on how to handle developments of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
He also elaborated on "his latest meetings and contacts" with
foreign officials on the Cyprus issue, said government spokesman
Michalis Papapetrou after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
During his recent visits to the U.S. and Britain, Clerides met
with British Prime Minister Tony Blair, U.N. Secretary-General's
Special Advisor on Cyprus Alvaro de Soto, U.S. Presidential
Emissary Alfred Moses, and British Special Representative Sir David
Hannay.
</P>
<P>
At the meetings, they discussed the decades-old Cyprus issue and
agreed that the next round of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks on
Cyprus should be more substantive and result-oriented, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The National Council vowed to continue seeking a federal
solution, within the framework set out by U.N. Security Council
resolutions, which provide for a bizonal, bicommunal federation in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
This solution, he said, must safeguard human rights and must
comply with the criteria for European Union membership.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens
coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the U.N. has been pushing for reunification of the
island under a bizonal, bicommunal federation formula, but all
efforts have failed to produce tangible results so far.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two sides on the tiny island have held two
rounds of proximity talks on Cyprus, the first round in New York
last December and the second in Geneva in February, with an aim to
prepare the ground for substantive talks which may lead to a
comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The third round of talks are scheduled to start on May 23 in New
York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Recognize Palestinian State by May: Israeli TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel will recognize
Palestinian independence after the two sides reach a framework
agreement for final-status issues by the end of May, Israel Channel
One television reported Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Citing a senior source familiar with the negotiations, the
report said that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak had inclined to
agree to "the establishment of a demilitarized Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
No Israeli official could be reached for comment on the report
as most Israelis are observing the Jewish Sabbath during Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the television report, the border between Israel
and the future independent Palestinian state, however, will not be
decided finally in the framework peace agreement expected to be
drafted by the May deadline.
</P>
<P>
The borderline is reportedly expected to be demarcated between
them by September 13, when the two sides are due to seal a final
peace treaty under the Sharm el Sheikh memorandum they signed last
September.
</P>
</TEXT>
