<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King to Visit Egypt Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
will pay a day-long visit to Egypt on Sunday for talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the Middle East peace process,
the Jordanian ambassador in Cairo said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Tarrad al-Fayez said the upcoming visit and the
summit come within the framework of continued coordinations between
the two leaders, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Abdullah will focus on the latest developments of
the Mideast peace process and the two countries' efforts aimed at
helping push forward the peace march on the Palestinian, Syrian and
Lebanese tracks, the news agency quoted al-Fayez as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli final status talks, which the two sides
have planned to conclude by September, on the thorniest issues
including the final borders, the fate of Jerusalem, refugees and
the Jewish settlements have made little progress.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli negotiations have been stalled since January
due to disputes over Israeli withdrawal from the Syrian Golan
Heights that the Jewish state occupied in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war
and control of the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will brief Abdullah on his talks in March with U.S.
President Bill Clinton in Washington, which dealt with, among other
things, the Arab-Israeli peace talks, the Jordanian diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abdullah will keep Mubarak posted on the results of
his recent visits to Belgium and Denmark, which also touched on the
peace process, Al-Fayez added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan, the first two Arab countries to make peace
with Israel, are keen on mediating in the peace talks between Arab
countries and the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
