<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Russia's Ratification of START II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a short statement, Clinton said that the approval of the
treaty by the Duma "builds on decades of cooperation between the
United States and Russia to reduce nuclear arms and clearly
advances the interests of both countries."
</P>
<P>
"START II will make our people safer and our partnership with a
democratic Russia stronger," he added.
</P>
<P>
"It will open the door to further significant steps to reduce
nuclear arms and the nuclear danger, a course that is strongly
supported by the international community and has strong bipartisan
support in the United States," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Russia's State Duma ratified the treaty in a vote earlier
Friday. The treaty, which was signed in 1993, was ratified by the
U.S. Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Now we and Russia can and must seize this opportunity to
intensify our discussions on both START III and the ABM (Anti-
Ballistic Missile) treaty, so we can take further concrete steps
this year to strengthen the security of the United States, Russia,
and indeed the whole world," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Under START II, the U.S. and Russia must cut the number of
nuclear warheads from 6,000 to no more than 3,500 on each side by
2007. The two countries agreed in 1997 to start their third round
of Strategic Arms Reduction Talks, or START III, once START II
enters into force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
