<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Summit Calls North Countries to Solve Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The foreign debt problem that
overwhelms Third World economies requires industrialized North
countries' participation for a lasting solution which pays
attention to structural causes generating this problem, said the
Final Declaration of the South Summit of the Group of 77.
</P>
<P>
The document says that during the last years, foreign debt-
underdevelopment vicious circle has worsened because the payments
required by creditors have become more onerous for many South
countries, including those with medium and low incomes.
</P>
<P>
The text underscores the need to look along with developed
countries an effective solution for the debt problem, whose actual
amount sums up to 2.5 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Third World leaders who have gathered in Havana since last
Wednesday asked for the concentration of medium income developing
countries' foreign debt reduction agreements and an amplification
of resources destined, for this purpose, to very indebted poor
countries.
</P>
<P>
At the same time they said that debt alleviation or
cancellation should not compromise funds destined for official
development assistance, which has been reduced to 0.22 percent of
industrialized countries' gross domestic income versus the 0.7
percent agreed upon in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Another aspect the declaration focuses on, to be approved
Friday at the closing of the South Summit, refers to the global
foreign debt strategy that must be followed, and regarding this
issue a finance, economics and development analysis was proposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Summit Approves South-South Political Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
These concepts are part of the declaration that will be passed
on Friday, at the closing of the five days event. This document is
a strategy the Third World has to fulfill in the new century in
order to favor the development of poor countries.
</P>
<P>
South-South cooperation is regarded by the participating
countries in the Havana event as an efficient mechanism capable of
mobilizing natural resources and human knowledge potentials of
this emerging nations.
</P>
<P>
Also, this sort of cooperation is regarded as a way of
complementing projects in force supported by assisting countries.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state recognize as well the need to overcome
factors that until now have limited the development of horizontal
collaboration, which faces as one of its main obstacles lack of
financial resources.
</P>
<P>
That is why the countries represented in the Havana summit
compromise to identify financing sources, and to design follow-up
mechanisms that help to comply with the agreements accorded by the
Group of 77.
</P>
<P>
Along with the General Declaration, the Action Program
containing over a hundred South-South cooperation projects in the
fields of health, education, science, technology and
communications among other are to be approved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-77 Summit Calls for Prompt General Acceptance of WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The declaration, approved by the heads of state of the
developing countries assembled at Havana, demands that a
transparent, simple and accelerated process of adhesion to the WTO
take place in agreement with this organization's laws and
dispositions.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the evolution of world trade during the last years,
the document says that market liberalization undertaken by many
developing countries and the role of the WTO have not translated
into the reality, nor guaranteed their full participation in the
multilateral trade system.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the document demands that the WTO carry out
an in-depth revision of the agreement on intellectual property
related to trade, an issue in which highly developed countries
have refrained from easing license and trade marks use, which in
general are in the hands of transnational companies headquartered
in the North.
</P>
<P>
As for trade barriers existing in rich countries, the G-77 text
denounces the use of environmental norms as a new form of
protectionism and proposes that matters related to this norms be
handled by competent international organizations and not by the
WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
