<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Havana Summit Calls for Stronger South Role in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The first South Summit is to
conclude here on Friday night with Third World leaders vowing to
unite as a group in fighting poverty, demanding a greater say in
world political and economic decision-making process, and joining
developed countries in technical revolution.
</P>
<P>
The South Summit, the largest gathering of heads of state and
government of the Group of 77 (G-77), is scheduled to issue two
final documents -- the Declaration and the Program of Plan -- at
the end of the three-day historic event.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 heads of state or government and delegations from 122 G-
77 countries all have one objective: to strengthen South-South
cooperation for common development in developing countries in
globalization.
</P>
<P>
The Summit, which opened here Wednesday following two-day
preparatory meetings, was held at the turn of century when many
developing countries are being marginalized in the tide of
globalization, which is characterized by trade, investment,
capital flows and advancements in information technology.
</P>
<P>
"Globalization has increased the vulnerability of those
countries of the South, which are in the process of being
integrated into the world economy," the South countries said in
the Program of Action.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Summit demands the establishment a just and fair
new international political and economic system, and a greater say
in multilateral lending institutions, such as the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund, the World Trade Organization and
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Our peoples have run out of patience," Cuban Foreign Minister
Felipe Perez Roque told a meeting of G-77 foreign ministers here
Tuesday. "For decades they have suffered broken promises and are
today living in an economic and social situation that is
increasingly serious and unsustainable."
</P>
<P>
"Nothing we say or do will have any true meaning for our
people unless we can significantly and quickly reduce the shameful
number of those who live in poverty, even as more people than ever
become millionaires," said Belize's Prime Minister Said Musa.
</P>
<P>
"One day, humankind will be called to account: How come you
never made no connection between growing poverty for the many and
booming wealth for a new?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the leaders joining Said are U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, South African President Thabo Mbeki who is also the
chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement, Vietnamese President Tran
Duc Long, Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid, Venezuelan
President Hugo Chavez, Palestine leader Yasser Araft, and
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the Summit was Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing,
head of the Chinese Government delegation. "
</P>
<P>
Describing the South Summit as "a grand, pioneering meeting,"
Li said, "In the interests of safeguarding world peace and
promoting development, let us look back over the past and forward
into the future and work together in a cooperative spirit to map
out a strategy for common development in the new century."
</P>
<P>
"The new century will present us both hope and difficulties,"
he said. "We people of developing countries have never been in
want of the courage to surmount difficulties or an undaunted
enterprising spirit."
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that as long as developing countries unite as
one and make tireless efforts, there will firmly stand a peaceful,
stable and prosperous South," he declared.
</P>
<P>
G-77, set up by 77 developing countries in Geneva in 1964, saw
its membership growing to 133 countries, but the original name was
retained because of its historic significance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest Third World coalition in the United Nations and
the largest grouping in the South, G-77 provides the means for the
developing world to articulate and promote its collective economic
interests and enhance its joint negotiating capacity on all major
international economic issues in the United Nations system, and
promote economic and technical cooperation among developing
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
