<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Countries Call for Fair Economic Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Member countries to attend the
first South Summit called Friday for creating a more just
international economic system.
</P>
<P>
In the final Declaration of the Summit approved by all the 133
member countries of the Group of 77 (G-77) here in the capital
city of Cuba, they said the process of globalization and
interdependence must not be used to weaken or re-interpret the
principle of international Law, in particular, sovereignty and
sovereign equality of States, independence, territorial integrity,
self-determination, non-interference in internal affairs,
reaffirming the right of all nations to choose their own political,
economic and social systems.
</P>
<P>
They called for the creation of a more just and equitable
international economic system that offers security for all people
and growing opportunities to raise their standard of living.
</P>
<P>
Globalization must be considered in the wider context of
development and in a globalized and interdependent world it is
more crucial than ever that developed countries act in solidarity
with the South and meet their historic responsibilities with
regard to the development of them, said the document.
</P>
</TEXT>
