<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania, Hungary Seek Legal Terms to Defiled Rivers Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Viktor Orban is in Bucharest for an one-day official visit at
the invitation of his Romanian counterpart Mugur Isarescu.
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything in our power to offset the damage
suffered by Hungary," the visiting Hungarian prime minister said,
stressing that this matter can be resolved only by legal ways.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian and Hungarian Governments have already negotiated
and signed an agreement over the environmental protection, which
has cleared the Hungarian Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Prime Minister Mugur Isarescu said for his part that
Romania has already asked the court to state who's responsible for
the damage and what the damages are. He said the only problem with
this agreement was the responsibility of the states in this field,
an issue which Romania pledged to solve, given the worldwide
developments in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Isarescu saw the bright side of the story, namely that the two
countries have agreed to cooperate in order to settle the problem.
</P>
<P>
"What matters is that the cooperation has come to life and the
problem will be pragmatically approached by monitoring the
ecological risk-prone areas in Romania and Hungary," Mugur
Isarescu said.
</P>
<P>
Mugur Isarescu said that ecological investments were highly
important and that Romania had broached the idea of winning loans
from the World Bank and the European Community for this purpose.
He said the response had been positive and supplementary funds
would come to help in protecting costly environmental projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
