<HEADLINE> Uganda's Ruling Party Urged to Convince People to Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has urged leaders of the ruling National Resistance Movement (NRM)
to convince people to vote in the forthcoming referendum.
</P>
<P>
He made the call while addressing a public rally in Mubende
District near Kampala Friday afternoon, according to a press
release from the President's Office.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, who is also chairman of the NRM, said that the
leaders and campaigners of the ruling party must explain clearly
to the public why the country should continue with the NRM system.
</P>
<P>
He reminded those at the rally of the major achievements made
by the NRM, including ridding the country of dictatorship,
maintaining democratic rule and reviving the economy.
</P>
<P>
These achievements were accomplished due to the internal
strength the NRM has built up within the country, the way it has
organized the economy and the support of many close friends it has
made outside the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that the massive support the NRM enjoys is
based on its performance since it came to power in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Under Uganda's Constitution, a referendum is to be held in June
to decide on the country's political system. There are several
systems which have been registered to participate in the
referendum, but the NRM is widely believed to be the winner.
</P>
