<HEADLINE> Canada to Launch Multimedia Satellite Payload </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Minister of Industry John
Manley announced a plan Friday to develop and launch a
communications satellite payload worth 109 million Canadian
dollars (about 74 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Ka band high-speed, multimedia communications payload is a
key part of the Anik F2 satellite to be launched in 2002 by Ottawa-
based satellite operator Telesat Canada at an expense of 600
million Canadian dollars (about 408 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A joint venture of the Canadian Space Agency, Telesat Canada
and two other Canadian companies, the project will provide cheaper,
faster and more highly effective communications services in North
America.
</P>
<P>
It will also expand access to tele-medicine, tele-learning,
tele-working, e-commerce, high-speed Internet and government
services to citizens throughout Canada.
</P>
<P>
Minister Manley said in his announcement of the project that
the country is enhancing its competitiveness in communications
services through "continuing support for leading-edge research and
development."
</P>
<P>
Telesat Canada's Anik F2 will be the first satellite in North
America to carry a digital on-board process. Direct economic
benefits from the Anik F2 Ka band multimedia satellite services
are projected at over 1 billion Canadian dollars (680 million U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
