<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak "Very Pessimistic" about Israeli-Syrian Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Friday issued the most pessimistic review about peace talks
with Syria since their negotiations broke off in January.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference of his Labor party ministers in Tel
Aviv, Barak said he is "very pessimistic" regarding the
negotiations, though he believed a very narrow crack is still left
on the door for a possible resumption, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving on Monday for a summit with U.S President Bill
Clinton in Washington, Barak only said he was not optimistic about
chances of reviving the talks.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations, which resumed last December after a 45-month
break, hit a snag again in January only after two rounds of
fruitless talks near Washington.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, the major mediator in the Syrian peace track, had drawn
his rein after his summit with Syrian president Hafez al-Assad in
Geneva on March 26 failed to make progress as expected.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the prospect of the talks, Clinton said the ball
was now in Syria's court, suggesting that he and Barak would wait
for Assad's answers to the Israeli proposal rather than concede to
more Syrian demands.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, the Syrian responses reached Washington till now are
not satisfactory for both Clinton and Barak.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Barak said he leaned to pull Israeli soldiers back
from south Lebanon by July on the basis of the United Nations
Security Council Resolution 425, indicating he nearly gave up all
hopes to reach a peace deal with Syria, the major power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution, adopted more than two decades ago, calls
for an immediate and unconditional Israeli withdrawal from all
Lebanese territory and a return of full sovereignty to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It is now used by Israel as a legitimate framework for a
unilateral withdrawal from its self-styled security zone in south
Lebanon, where growing casualties of Israeli occupation troops
prompted the cabinet determination last month to exit with or
without a deal with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel had exchange views with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan, and leaders of France, Canada and other countries, about the
possibility to extending authority of the current U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon to fill the vacuum after Israel troops leave.
</P>
<P>
Barak also warned against any attempt to "test Israel's
response" by lobbing missiles into northern Israel. It was reported
that Hezbollah guerrillas and other groups fighting to end Israeli
occupation in Lebanon had begun to recruit fighters from the 300,
000 Palestinian refugees in Lebanese camps.
</P>
<P>
Barak also promised more economic and security measures for
settlers near the border with Lebanon, in an effort to placate
their worries for possible cross-border guerrilla attack after the
Israeli pullout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
