<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Defends "Legal Violence" in Islam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei on Friday strongly defended "legal violence" by the
Islamic regime in cracking down on riots to safeguard security.
</P>
<P>
"Legal violence is not only good but necessary" and the Islamic
regime will act "with strength and violence" against all those
resorting to force, aggression, and violation of the law, Khamenei
said.
</P>
<P>
"Legal repression is indispensable because without it there
would be no way of maintaining order and security," Khamenei said
at the Friday prayers at downtown Tehran University.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei made the remarks amid mounting political tensions after
reformists allied with President Mohammad Khatami scored a victory
over the conservatives in the February parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
"If you do not check this sort of violence, you would face
growing violations in the society," he added.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to protests last week in the northwestern city
of Khalkhal, which took place after the conservative Guardians
Council overturned election results to deprive a reformist
candidate of victory and hand the seat to his conservative rival.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of people have been jailed after one of the
demonstrations turned violent, with protestors smashing public
buildings and setting vehicles on fire.
</P>
<P>
"One must act in accordance with the law, even if one has a
complaint," Khamenei said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the people to safeguard national unity and
security, saying that "in the absence of these two factors, the
government would not be able to cope with the economic, social and
cultural problems." 
</P>
