<HEADLINE> Rwandan Genocide Victims to Be Compensated with Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Some of the Rwandan victims in
the 1994 genocide will be compensated with community service since
not all convicts own valuable property, according to Rwandan News
Agency report on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said a study carried out in several prisons, showed
that 67 percent of the convicts were ready to pay compensation in
terms of community service, while 42 percent wanted to pay in
cash.
</P>
<P>
"Compensation should be paid if reconciliation is to be
attained and improve social wellbeing of genocide survivors", said
Frederick Mutagwera, the President of Ibuka association (a
genocide survivors association).
</P>
<P>
" People who had a hand in the genocide are ready to pay for
their crimes in a bid to reconcile", Prof. Gasibirege of the
National University of Rwanda said.
</P>
<P>
Gacaca courts (participatory justice) are set to establish a
prioritisation system for genocide victims supposed to receive
compensation; in order that, all deserving victims may benefit.
</P>
<P>
A number of cases have been heard and compensation orders
issued by court but no single compensation has been paid to
deserving victims. Most of the genocide perpetuators do not have
valuable property to pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
Some half million Rwandans were killed in the genocide in 1994.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
