<HEADLINE> S.African Economy to Benefit from Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The privatization of
state-owned assets will generate at least 40 billion rand (about
6.6 billion U.S. dollars) for South Africa over the next three
years, said Public Enterprises Minister Jeff Radebe in Cape Town
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of money will come from foreign direct investment in
the "big four" state-owned enterprises, namely Eskom (
electricity), Transnet (transport), Telkom (telecommunication) and
Denel (the country's sole arms manufacturer), he said.
</P>
<P>
Introducing debate on his department's budget vote in the
National Assembly, Radebe said the government's restructuring
program will be completed by 2004.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program will ensure that the government is
committed to enterprise restructuring, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a detailed restructuring plan and timetable has been
submitted to Cabinet and will be made public in May.
</P>
<P>
According to the restructuring plan, Transnet will be broken up
into a series of stand-alone transport businesses within 36 months
and Denel will be corporatized by October this year. 
