It seems that in most cases the causative organism was not the
cholera vibrio, she said, citing that out of a sample of 300
people suffering from diarrhoea, it was found that only 15 percent
of them had the cholera vibrio.
</P>
<P>
She said most of the deaths could have been avoided if those
concerned had sought medical help immediately.
</P>
<P>
"People only go to the health units when they are already in a
serious condition," she said. "Sometimes it is difficult to do
anything because of the advanced state of the disease, and the
person ends up losing his life."
</P>
<P>
Ferreira urged Maputo residents to go to health unit as soon as
they start suffering from diarrhoea or fevers, since these could
be the symptoms of cholera or malaria.
</P>
<P>
The people should remain in a state of alert and maintain
maximum personal hygiene, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Introduce Value Added Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14(Xinhua) -- The Rwanda Revenue Authority (RRA)
has declared that it will commence the Value Added Tax (VAT)
system in the country on November 1, 2000, Rwanda News Agency
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mutabingwa Aloys, RRA officer in charge of the technical and
legal affairs of the system, was quoted as saying, "this tax
serves the purpose of raising the much needed revenue for
government in the easiest and least painful way, by distributing
the tax burden amongst all consumers in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Putting the VAT tax system in place has been one of the
objectives of this year's National Budget, Aloys said, noting that
it had earlier been planned to commence in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Donald Kaberuka, Minister of Finance and Economic Planning,
recently indicated that full participation of Rwanda in the zero
tariff regime of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
would be delayed for the purpose of putting such institutions as
VAT in place.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda's neighbors, namely Uganda, Tanzania,and Kenya have
already put the taxation system in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
