<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrean Refugees in Sudan to Be Repatriated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea, Sudan and the U.N. High
 Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) have recently signed an
agreement on the repatriation of some 160,000 Eritrean refugees in
Sudan over the next six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
Some of the refugees have been in exile in Sudan for as long as
30 years and their return is based on strictly voluntary nature,
said Director Albert-Alain Peters of the UNHCR Africa Bureau here
on Friday at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He told the reporters that the UNHCR country representatives
across Africa, together with the directors of regional offices in
Abidjan, Nairobi and Pretoria, just concluded a three-day meeting
to review their progress in operations in the Kenyan capital
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The UNCHR officials discussed the challenges they are facing,
including population displacement due to drought in the Horn of
Africa, the best care and asylum for those long-staying refugees
and the difficulty of raising funds for African operations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, they also decided to create rapid-response
teams for various tasks on the continent, Peters said.
</P>
<P>
Due to fighting and hunger, the number of refugees in southern
Sudan fleeing to neighboring Kenya and Uganda has doubled in the
past month, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to UNHCR statistics, by the end of 1999, there had
been 3.52 million refugees across the African continent, and this
has not included the 941,100 internally displaced people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
