<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly Half Lebanese Live Below Poverty Line: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A survey indicates that nearly half
Lebanese families live in "ultra poverty" and more than two-thirds
are enduring below-average living conditions.
</P>
<P>
The survey, made by the General Labor Confederation (GLC) and
released on newspapers Friday, showed that 48 percent of families
were living under "ultra poverty" line.
</P>
<P>
The line was defined as a 592 U.S. dollar monthly salary for a
family of five. Meanwhile 68 percent of families live "at or
around" below-average conditions, which constitute a monthly salary
of 1,100 dollars for a five-member family without educational
expenses.
</P>
<P>
The GLC called on the government to take a "serious and radical
change in its economic policies" to redress the situation.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that, in the period between 1966 and now,
the prices of goods and services have increased 4,954 times. The
increase was more noticeable on certain spending items like
education compared to others like food.
</P>
<P>
But the wages and salaries which rose by only 2,069 percent from
1966 to 2000. The minimum wage in Lebanon presently stands at 200
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Stresses Importance of Maintaining Talent Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Securing a healthy national
talent pool of highly trained scientists, technicians and
engineers is important in achieving national goals, said Neal Lane,
the U.S. president's science adviser, in a report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the report titled "Ensuring a strong U.S. scientific,
technical, and engineering workforce in the 21st century," Lane
said an adequate reservoir of scientific, technical and
engineering (ST&AMP;E) resources, including human resources, is
indispensable in achieving important national goals, such as a
growing economy, strong defense, healthy population, safe
environment, and high quality of life for citizens.
</P>
<P>
Lane said many types of ST&AMP;E jobs are among the fastest growing
in the U.S. workforce, to the point that demand for workers has
outstripped supply and unemployment in science and engineering
occupations is quite low: about one-half the rate for the entire U.
S. workforce, a rate which itself is at historic low levels.
</P>
<P>
If current trends persist, Lane said, the United States may not
have all of the talent it will need to enable the innovation
process that has given America a strong economy and high quality
of life.
</P>
<P>
"There is already evidence that worker shortages are limiting
economic growth, and industry has repeatedly called for increases
in the visa quotas that allow technically skilled non-immigrants
to work in the United States," Lane said
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, worldwide socioeconomic trends and educational
developments will challenge the preeminence of the United States
in science, technology and engineering -- and challenge its
economic strength.
</P>
<P>
Lane cautioned that because other nations also recognize the
importance to sustained economic growth of a highly skilled
workforce, there is fierce international competition for workers
in high-technology growth areas, such as electronics and
information technology, and in other industrial sectors that
increasingly depend on advances in these areas.
</P>
<P>
Lane concluded that if the United States is to maintain
leadership across the frontiers of science, the nation must draw
upon its own full talent pool to ensure its scientific and
technical workplace reflects the face of America.
</P>
<P>
"Since it takes many years to train a scientist or engineer,
the United States must invest now to guarantee the availability of
a skilled and competent workforce for the 21st century, and must
not only educate future ST&AMP;E workers but also provide continuing
education and retraining opportunities," said Lane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
