<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Supreme Leader Rejects U.S.-Style Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei on Friday rejected any U.S.-style reforms, saying that
Iran's reforms are based on Islam and the Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The political or social reforms that the U.S. government wants
to see in Iran are naturally incompatible with Islam and are
certainly despised by Iranian people, Khamenei said at the Friday
prayers in downtown Tehran University.
</P>
<P>
He said the Islamic regime needs reforms in the administrative,
judicial and economic fields as long as there are the slightest
flaws in any aspect of the society, the official Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, he claimed that Washington was "opposed to true reforms
in Iran."
</P>
<P>
"All they want are U.S.-style reforms," he asserted.
</P>
<P>
Iran's moderate President Mohammad Khatami has been pushing for
a variety of social, political and economic reforms since his 1997
election, but his agenda has frequently been stymied by
conservatives, who dominate most of the sensitive state organs.
</P>
<P>
The country has been experiencing high tensions and factional
struggles following the overwhelming victory of the reformists
allied with Khatami in the February parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
A prominent reformist advisor to Khatami was seriously wounded
in an abortive assassination attempt in March, and pressures have
been mounting on the pro-reform press as a number of newspaper
managing directors and journalists were summoned by hard-line
courts.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei accused the U.S. of "seeking to inculcate their own
interpretations of reforms into the minds of Iranian people for
purely private purposes."
</P>
<P>
The Americans do not really advocate reforms in Iran because
they are basically against the 1979 Islamic revolution at its
foundation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that some people in Iran were only repeating the
wishes of the Americans, threatening to "divulge the names of those
people who were promoting the schemes of the country's enemies."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Bangladesh to Exercise Restraint on Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- India and neighboring
Bangladesh have agreed to exercise utmost restraint on their
border and curb the menace of smuggling and trafficking in women
and children and narcotics from and to each side.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a five-day biannual conference on
border management between India's Border Security Force (BSF) and
Bangladesh Rifles, which concluded here Friday, the BSF said in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
The existing mutual cooperation between the two forces has
helped in sustaining peace and tranquillity in the border areas,
the release added.
</P>
<P>
Border force officials of the two countries signed a joint
record of discussions Friday at the conclusion of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
BSF Director General E. N. Rammohan will visit Bangladesh later
this year at the invitation of his counterpart, Major General
Fazlur Rahman, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
