<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Evolves From Unipolar to Multipolar Singapore Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Minister for Foreign
Affairs S. Jayakumar said here Friday that the world evolves from
a unipolar toward a multipolar one and Asia and Europe should join
their efforts to strengthen the linkages and cooperation between
the two important regions.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar, who doubles as the minister for law, made the
remarks at the opening dinner of the Third Europe-Asia Forum
attended by some 50 representatives from Asia Europe Meeting (ASEM)
member countries for discussions on economic recovery in Asia
following the Asian financial crisis, new economic development in
Europe, prospects for Asia-Europe cooperation and topics
concerning the ASEM summit to be held in Seoul, South Korea, in
October.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar told the forum, which will end Saturday, that East
Asia and Europe should cooperate to facilitate the transition to a
multipolar world from a unipolar one following the end of the Cold
War as the world is likely to evolve in this century toward a
multipolar world with the United States, the European Union (EU),
East Asia, Latin America and Russia as poles.
</P>
<P>
He noted that by 1996 combined strength of the 10 East Asian
countries and the United States each accounted for 25 percent of
the world gross domestic product and the EU 29 percent of the
world economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the two-way trade between the EU and East Asia was
greater than that between the EU and the United States and the EU
economy is larger than that of the United States, he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of globalization, Jayakumar said Asia and Europe must
brace themselves to embrace globalization, to seize the
opportunities of the new economy, to overcome challenges and to
contribute to the creation of a multi-cultural world.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Third ASEM Summit, the minister expected some
possible deliverables around ASEM's three pillars -- business and
economics, people to people cooperation and political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
In the field of economics, he said the first is for all ASEM
countries to strongly reaffirm their commitment to the
multilateral trading system, which the WTO ministerial meeting at
Seattle, the United States, last year failed to launch, and the
second is to strengthen the existing Europe-Asia Business Forum.
</P>
<P>
On people to people cooperation, he urged more efforts to forge
greater linkages between people in Asia and Europe and
fundamentally reform their education system.
</P>
<P>
On political dialogue, Jayakumar suggested that ASEM's
political dialogue should begin with global political and security
issues which are of concern to all ASEM partners.
</P>
<P>
ASEM came into being four years ago when 16 EU leaders and 10
East Asian leaders held their first summit in Bangkok, Thailand.
That summit launched the process of building a new comprehensive
partnership between East Asia and Western Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
