<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Surge in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices jumped 0.
7 percent in March, the biggest gain in almost a year, led by
sharp increases in gasoline and other energy prices, the Labor
Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the department's Consumer Price Index, the most
closely watched inflation gauge, was the largest since last April,
when consumer prices also rose by 0.7 percent. Many analysts were
anticipating the consumer prices would rise 0.5 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
The surge stemmed from a 4.9 percent increase in energy prices,
the largest since last April.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, the "core"
rate of inflation rose 0.4 percent, the strongest increase in five
years. The core rate rose twice as fast as many analysts were
expecting. The government said rising prices for housing,
transportation and household furnishings accounted for most of the
increase.
</P>
<P>
In February, consumer prices rose 0.5 percent, reflecting
sharply higher energy costs, while the core inflation rate went up
by a mild 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The consumer inflation report comes one day after the
government said inflation at the wholesale level in March shot up
by 1 percent, but the spike was limited to higher energy prices.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, consumer prices have been rising at an annual
rate of 5.8 percent, compared with 2.7 percent for all of 1999.
The pickup in this year's prices mostly reflects rising energy
costs.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates five times since
June 30 to slow the supercharged economy and keep inflation under
control. Given the outlook for strong continuing growth, many
analysts believe the central bank will nudge up rates again on May
16.
</P>
<P>
In another report, the Commerce Department said that U.S.
businesses boosted their stockpiles of goods on shelves and
backlogs by 0.5 percent and sales grew by 0.3 percent in February.
Both figures were in line with analysts' expectations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
