<HEADLINE> Some 1.3 Million Need Food Aid in Southeast Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- At least 1.3 million drought
victims are waiting for relief in the Ethiopian town of Gode, some
600 kilometers southeast of the capital Addis Ababa, Catherine
Bertini, executive director of the Rome-based World Food Program
(WFP), said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bertini, who visited the town on Wednesday, told a press
conference that many people in the town are dying of
malnourishment,
</P>
<P>
The WFP chief said she could not give specific number of death
in the drought stricken area.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said that about 400 people in and around
Gode died daily in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
According to Bertini, the Ethiopian regional government and
many non- governmental organizations have established relief
centers to distribute relief food and medicine to the drought
victims.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts by the aid workers, many people including
 children who were struggling for lives have survived, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We are making assessment as soon as possible about drought
situation in Ethiopia," Bertini said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to security problems that are believed to hamper the
relief operation, Bertini said that she had consulted with
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi over the problem.
</P>
<P>
Bertini said to use troops to protect relief operation in some
dangerous areas would be "very very last choice".
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of expanding airlift relief operation in the
drought- stricken areas, the WFP chief said although the
International Committee of Red Cross has begun airlifting food and
medicine to Gode, it could not be the base for the relief program
because there are too many people waiting to be served.
</P>
<P>
Bertini, sent by United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to
make field assessment of the current drought situation in the Horn
of Africa, will leave for Djibouti on Saturday and visit Eritrea
and Kenya later on.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 16 million people in the Horn of
Africa are affected by the drought and facing starvation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
