<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Warns Member States of PCB Disposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission warned
on Friday 14 of the European Union's 15 member states of the
problem of polychlorinated biphenyls disposal.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the union, sent warning
letters to all member states but Finland for their failure to
comply with the commission's provisions about PCB disposal.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, only Finland abided by the requirement of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Polychlorinated biphenyls are highly toxic and persistent
hazardous chemicals that have the tendency to bio-accumulate in
living tissues.
</P>
<P>
"Strict control of PCBs is essential," said EU Environment
Commissioner Margot Wallstrom, "particularly to respond to the
public's concern and prevent these substances from finding their
way into the food chain."
</P>
<P>
Though the production of polychlorinated biphenyls has been
banned and their use has been restricted, PCBs are still widely
present in transformers and capacitors where they are used as
dielectric fluids.
</P>
<P>
PCBs are also used in building materials, carbonless copy paper,
lubricants, surface coatings, adhesives, plasticizers, sealants
and inks.
</P>
<P>
The commission has asked the union member states to streamline
their legislation on the decontamination and disposal of equipment
containing PCBs and to compile inventories of equipment with PCB
volumes above a certain threshold and to report back to the
commission before September 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
