<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ratification of START-II Meets Russia's Interests: Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The ratification of the 1993
Russian-U.S. second-phase Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START-
II) meets Russia's national interests, said Russian President-
elect Vladimir Putin following the approval of the pact by the
State Duma on Friday.
</P>
<P>
After the voting, Putin told the press in the Duma that the
decision "fully meets the national interests of Russia and permits
it not only to keep its nuclear force, but also channel the
necessary funds for maintaining the combat readiness of
conventional armed forces."
</P>
<P>
"Not merely do I welcome it, but I actively support the Duma
decision," he said.
</P>
<P>
On further steps in this sphere, he said the ball was now in
the American court.
</P>
<P>
"Our counterparts in the talks should take further steps. We
are developing good conditions for strengthening international
security," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia does not need a new arms race at all, Putin stressed
when he showed up in the parliament before the voting to urge
deputies to ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"Putting off the ratification of START-II, on which the future
of our strategic nuclear forces depends, would be undesirable and
harmful and lead to absurd expenses," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, with START-II or without, Russia's heavy rockets will
have to be destroyed in seven to 10 years because of their
degradation, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, if Russia ratifies the treaty, the balance of global
forces will be maintained and Washington will be compelled to
ratify START-III, he added.
</P>
<P>
"If, in the wake of our ratification of START-II linked to the
1997 agreements on differentiating strategic and non-strategic ABM
systems, the United States dismantles the 1972 ABM Treaty, we will
pull out of the system of treaty relations on the limitation of
and control over strategic and conventional arms, "said Putin.
</P>
<P>
"We may also think of revising our commitments on tactical arms,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
Ratification will make it possible for Russia to reduce
excessive costs and focus limited funds on new arms so as to make
the armed forces more efficient and combat-ready in light of the
fact that Russia now faces local conflicts, Putin said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
