<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Cases to Rise 70 Percent by 2015 in Canada: Society </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of cancer cases will
rise by 70 percent by 2015 in Canada despite remarkable progress
achieved in fighting the disease, the Canadian Cancer Society
warned in its 12th annual report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The society expects 132,100 new cases of cancer this year, up 2
percent from the estimated 129,300 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Canada is facing more cancer cases because of its aging
population and other factors involving heredity, hormonal changes,
food, environment, lack of exercise and smoking.
</P>
<P>
Smoking and obesity are linked to about 60 percent of all
cancers in the report, which pointed out in particular that,
smoking is the reason why lung cancer remains a top killer disease
among both sexes.
</P>
<P>
Lung cancer incidence and mortality rates among women continue
to climb and are almost five times as high as those of 1971. Up to
8,400 women are expected to be diagnosed with lung cancer this
year with a death toll of 7,000.
</P>
<P>
Smoking rates are still increasing in the 15-to-19-year age
group and it is higher among young women than young men, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the society stated that Canadians are gaining ground
on several fronts in the battle against cancer as death rates drop
for children, women with breast cancer and men with lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to better treatments, death rates for childhood cancers
have fallen by more than 50 percent since the early 1950s, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Very few children survived childhood leukemia 40 years ago, but
today approximately 80 percent of Canadian children suffering from
the disease are alive five years after diagnosis, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Breast cancer death rates have dropped by 25 percent among
women aged 50 to 69 since 1985 and are at the lowest level since
1950. The trend is expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
Lung cancer death rates among men have declined by 24 percent
since 1986 as a result of a drop in smoking rates that began two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The society described early detection as the key to treating
cancer, citing a more accurate mammography and a new form of
prostate specific antigen testing as encouraging work in this area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Offers New Aid to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union approved a
humanitarian aid to Mozambique on Friday to assist victims of the
recent floods in the African country.
</P>
<P>
The aid, amounting to 5.58 million euros (5.35 million U.S.
dollars), will be channeled through the European Community
Humanitarian Office and will fund relief work for the next six
months.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European bloc has so far allocated 9.73 million
euros (9.34 million dollars) to the African country since the
flooding.
</P>
<P>
The new humanitarian aid will cover acute emergency assistance
to those affected in specific areas and the aid includes basic
curative care, water supply and sanitation as well as cholera
contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
The number of people in need in Mozambique are estimated at 100,
000, including 20,000 children under the age of five, mainly in
the worst hit province of Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union will continue to assist with both emergency
and development aid for as long as the country needs our support,"
said Poul Nielson, EU commissioner for humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
On top of this humanitarian aid, an initial amount of 21
million euros (20 million dollars) has been released to address
the medium-term needs for rehabilitation of the afflicted areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
