<HEADLINE> Contracted Overseas Investment in Guangdong Shows Sharp Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Contracted overseas investment
in South China's Guangdong province hit 2.32 billion US dollars in
the first quarter this year, 41.3 percent up in a year-on-year
comparison, a spokesman for foreign trade in the province said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"Overseas investors are robustly active and the number of new
contracts of overseas investments has been skyrocketing," Liao
Guoji said in a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The province bordering Hong Kong netted a total of 3,356
overseas investment contracts in the first quarter of 2000, a jump
of 41.3 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Overseas funds actually put into use in the first three months
reached 2.5 billion US dollars, down 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Of the new contracts, 853 were overseas direct investments (ODI)
, 43.6 percent up over last year, and ODI volume reached 1.83
billion US dollars, a 54.3 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
The sharp increase in overseas investment contracts this year
was a U-turn from the past two years, when the province was deeply
affected by the Asian financial crisis, Liao said.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investments in Guangdong mainly came from Hong Kong,
Macao, Taiwan, and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
