<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels Release Hostages in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The extremist Muslim rebel group,
Abu Sayyaf, released Friday two of their 31 hostages in the
southern Philippines after receiving 100 sacks of rice delivered
by the government, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, National Security Adviser Alexander
Aguirre confirmed the release of the two young girls held by the
Muslim rebels in Basilan, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
According to Aguirre, one of two girls is 11 years old and the
other nine. He said the release of the two hostages was due to the
collective effort of a mediation team.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three people, mostly teachers and students, were seized
by the Abu Sayyaf group on March 20, after a brief encounter
between the rebel group and the government forces.
</P>
<P>
"With the sending of the mediation team, the Basilan Crisis
Management Committee (CMC) had complied with the initial demands
of the Abu Sayyaf as a show of our desire to resolve the problem
through peaceful means," Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
As this developed, the Abu Sayyaf group has reportedly made
known their demands in exchange for the release of all the
remaining 29 hostages still in their hands.
</P>
<P>
Among their demands are the delivery of 200 sacks of rice and
release of their comrades held at the Basilan jail, media reports
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Aguirre, the peaceful efforts of the Basilan CMC
have resulted in the release of 26 hostages, including relatives
of Abu Sayyaf head Khaddafy Janjalani. Janjalani's relatives were
held captive by another Muslim group in retaliation for the Abu
Sayyaf hostage-taking move last month.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, there are still 39 hostages remaining in the hands
of the two groups, Aguirre said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
