<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Food Situation Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- As the Horn of Africa
especially Ethiopia was being hit by a severe famine, Tanzania
said its the food situation in the 1999/2000 season is stable.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Agriculture and Cooperatives William
Kusila was quoted by local newspaper Business Times on Friday as
saying that the Strategic Grain Reserve (SGR) was 103,000 tons,
the highest ever record.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on earlier reports that Tanzania was facing a
shortage of at least 350,000 tons of foodstuffs, Kusial said they
only took into account the stock of maize without considering
other cereals.
</P>
<P>
"Some times food shortages is exaggerated due to giving little
consideration to other cereals !- in fact, we have plenty of other
cereals," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kusila said that apart from the Central and Lake Victoria zones
being threatened by severe drought, Tanzania anticipates a good
field performance in other areas.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on the farmers to use the current rains to
capitalize on drought-resistant crops like cassava, millet and
sweet potatoes.
</P>
<P>
He said a long-term solution to curb food shortages in the
future "can be achieved only when farmers match government efforts
in keeping enough stocks during good harvests-rather than using
precious grains to make local brews for cultural dances, etc".
</P>
<P>
In a recent report on the Food Supply Situation and Crop
Prospects in sub-Saharan Africa, the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization said that nearly 16 million people need emergency
food aid in drought-stricken East Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The number of people needing assistance could increase, as
crop weather forecasts are discouraging," it said.
</P>
<P>
In drought-stricken Ethiopia, 8 million people face severe food
shortage.
</P>
<P>
Kenya also has to take care of 2.7 million of its people who
are in need of food assistance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
