<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Firm on Quitting COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has reaffirmed its
decision to quit the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA), the local Guardian newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Industry and Commerce Iddi Simba told a visiting
COMESA delegation on Thursday that it was not in the best
interests of Tanzania to be simultaneously a member of the East
African Community (EAC), the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) and COMESA.
</P>
<P>
"COMESA, SADC and EAC are all regional bodies with common goals
of establishing a common market and ultimately, if we can, a
common currency," Simba said in the designated new capital of
Dodoma in central Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Tanzania could not remain in all the three
regional blocs because it would have to adopt three individual
stands when negotiating with other regional organization and the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
In his reply, head of the COMESA delegation and the Chairman of
COMESA Council of Ministers Nicholas Biwott said the regional
grouping had made tremendous progress in addressing problems
facing Tanzania and many other members.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania is one of the founder members of COMESA, and like
many countries, it has concerns on its national interests," said
Biwott, who is also Kenya's Minister for Tourism, Trade and
Industry. "That is why COMESA is doing everything possible to
address these concerns."
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Industry Moses
Ali said that Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni had agreed to
persuade Tanzania to remain a member of COMESA.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, COMESA Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said
in Nairobi that Tanzania's decision to quit COMESA has not been
approved.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said Tanzania had reasons other than the concern that
deeper tariff cuts under COMESA's zero tariff rate program would
adversely affect its revenues and undermine local industries.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Tanzania's decision to quit the regional bloc
has raised fears that other COMESA members, who have dual
membership with SADC, may want out due to the problem of
duplication.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania announced decision to pull out of the 21-nation COMESA
in July last year because of a plan to reduce tariffs for member
countries by 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
COMESA leaders agreed in May last year to cut internal tariffs
to 10 percent of prior levels, and restated their aim to phase out
tariffs among member states by October 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foot-and-mouth Disease Cases Found in S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea found new cases of foot-
and-mouth disease Friday in Hongsong, South Chungchong Province, 1.
5 kilometers from where the first case of the epidemic was
discovered.
</P>
<P>
Epidemic control authorities said three of the 21 heads of
cattle raised in a farm in Hongsong showed foot-and-mouth virus
positive.
</P>
<P>
It is the ninth time for the local authorities to spot the
disease in Hongsong alone, according to the Yonhap News.
</P>
<P>
This brings the total number of such cases in the country to 57.
The disease, dubbed Livestock AIDS, causes blisters on the mouth
and hoofs of livestock.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has destroyed and buried all cattle and pigs within
a 20-kilometer radius of the affected area since the first case
was found in Paju, Kyonggi province, at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
Japan and China's Taiwan have suspended import of livestock and
meat from South Korea while the United States and Australia halted
import of dairy products from the country.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has confirmed that the epidemic is of the same type
which swept Taiwan a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
