<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Justice Department declined to take action Thursday
after the great-uncle of Elian Gonzalez defied a government order
and refused to surrender the 6-year-old boy, pushing the
international custody dispute into another day amid escalating
tension in Miami and mounting anger from Elian's Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday delivered the most
vigorous and sustained defense yet of the scandals that have
marred his administration, saying that he does not want or need
pardon for possible perjury charges and that he is still waiting
for journalists to report that the Whitewater investigation "was a
lie and a fraud from the beginning."
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- The UN Security Council Thursday approved a streamlined arms
inspection commission for Iraq, which has belittled the plan.
Russia warned that it would be watching for any inspector who
might be troublesome to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
-- Texas Governor George W. Bush met with a dozen gay
Republicans Thursday and said that he was a "better person," but
he was still opposed to gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The Nasdaq dropped 92.85 points, or 2.46 percent, to 3676.78
after spending most of the day in positive territory. The Dow
Jones industrials also weakened, falling 201.58 to 10923.55.
Market volatility has been extreme, partly because of momentum
investing and Internet.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. House Republicans Thursday passed a 1.83 trillion
dollars budget largely on party lines, and the Senate is due to
quickly follow suit. The spending plan is intended to provide
ammunition for fall races, but many backfire. 
</P>
