<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Over 10,000 Firms Operating in Pudong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By the end of 1999, 5,942 companies from 67 countries and
regions had invested more than 29.4 billion U.S. dollars in Pudong,
with some 100 of the world's 500 leading multinationals among them.
</P>
<P>
In 1999 alone, big names such as Bell, GM, Hewlett-Packard, and
Lucent, as well as a number of other corporations, added
additional investment totaling 377 million U.S. dollars to their
holdings there.
</P>
<P>
In most cases, multinationals chose large enterprises in
Shanghai as their partners, giving a boost to industrial
restructuring in the city and revitalizing a number of loss-making
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, more than 5,180 firms from other parts of
China have established subsidiaries in Pudong. By the end of 1999,
their registered capital in the area had amounted to 19.4 billion
yuan (about 2.34 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Wenzhou People's Electronic Appliance Group established a
production base in Pudong with an investment of 100 million yuan,
while Chunlan, Shanshan, Hongdou, and other well-known Chinese
companies have established research and development centers in the
area.
</P>
<P>
After ten years of development, Pudong has created several
pillar industries dealing in electronic information, automobiles,
pharmaceuticals, opto-electro-mechanical integration,
petrochemicals, and consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
Pudong's gross domestic product climbed to 80 billion yuan in
1999 from six billion yuan a decade ago, and goods made in Pudong
have entered more than 130 countries and regions worldwide. Last
year, the area's exports reached 6.67 billion U.S. dollars, up 23
percent over 1998.
</P>
<P>
Investors say Pudong not only offers tax incentives, but now
also has a world-class investment environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang to Help 60,000 Disabled Out of Poverty This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The coastal province of Zhejiang in
east China will double efforts to make sure that some 60,000 poor
disabled have access to the basic necessities of life through
special projects this year, said a local welfare official today.
</P>
<P>
This goal will be realized through a special project to help
these disabled people get fund and master techniques necessary for
starting their own businesses, the official said.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 local people have pledged to take part in the
project by helping 10,000 disabled people engage in planting,
processing and cottage industries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Through this effort, the disabled will learn new techniques and
be able to earn their own livings, he added.
</P>
<P>
Among the two million disabled people in Zhejiang, five percent
of the province's population, more than 200,000 have now escaped
poverty and have regular jobs.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to aid from governmental departments, social groups, and
individuals from all walks of life, the number of poor disabled
people in the province has decreased from 400,000 two decades ago
to 145,000 at present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
