<HEADLINE> Macao to Become Link Between China and Portuguese-Speaking Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- China will make Macao a transfer
station and exchange center of economic and trade ties between
China and Portuguese-speaking countries, Assistant Minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation He Xiaowei said here today.
</P>
<P>
He told participants of the Beijing-Macao International
Business Forum that Macao's position as a bridge linking the
mainland and Portuguese-speaking countries offers it a unique
advantage for developing foreign trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China's trade volume with Portuguese-speaking countries last
year was only 2.5 billion U.S. dollars, and the investment scale
remained small.
</P>
<P>
"China and Portuguese-speaking countries share broad prospects
in trade, investment, contract engineering and labor cooperation,"
he said, pointing out that Macao will undoubtedly function as a
vital link when China enhances ties with those countries.
</P>
<P>
Macao and Portuguese-speaking countries, which have ties for
many years, maintain a steady flow of information back and forth,
he explained.
</P>
<P>
He added that Macao, as a formal member of the World Trade
Organization, has advantages in market access, finance and
insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
