<HEADLINE> Death Sentence Given to Kidnapper in East China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Convicted kidnapper Liang Kunmin
has been given the death sentence by a local court in east China's
Jiangsu Province for abduction and rape of five women, the
Ministry of Public Security said today.
</P>
<P>
Liang, a 27-year-old peasant from southwest China's Guizhou
Province, has also been stripped of his political rights for life
and all his personal belongings.
</P>
<P>
In the period between March 1998 and June 1999, Liang kidnapped
four women from Guizhou Province and sold them to buyers in east
China's Anhui Province at prices of 6,400 yuan, 5,000 yuan, 4,000
yuan and 2,900 yuan.
</P>
<P>
On September 4, 1999, he abducted a young girl, surnamed Tang,
taking her to east China's Jiangsu Province where he planned to
sell her. Local residents tipped off police of Liang's plans, and
he was apprehended by police.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Chinese police kicked off a nationwide anti-
abudction campaign by using advanced technology including DNA
analysis
</P>
</TEXT>
