<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Govt to Take Measures to Control Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Lily Yam, secretary for the
environment and food of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), said here Friday that the SAR government has a
comprehensive package of measures to deal with air pollution
problems.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after delivering a speech to an
Australian Chamber of Commerce luncheon, Yam said Hong Kong's
capital spending on the environment increased from 610 million HK
dollars (78,205 U.S. dollars) in 1989 to nearly 4 billion HK
dollars (512,820 U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
She also pointed out that the government has various measures
to deal with air pollution problems, including a plan to convert
taxis here to the use of liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) as fuel.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure the smooth implementation of the LPG taxi conversion
scheme, we need to provide sufficient LPG filling facilities in
convenient locations," she said.
</P>
<P>
On the use of ultra-low sulfur diesel, she said Hong Kong
already has the most stringent fuel and vehicle emission standards
in Asia and the government is in support of the idea of
introducing ultra-low sulfur diesel for diesel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Also, the government actively supports other initiatives to
develop clean fuel and related technologies, including trolley
buses, natural gas and, in the longer run, fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
On the enforcement front, she said the police are stepping up
action against smoky vehicles and the Customs and Excise
Department has intensified its attack against the use of illicit
diesel.
</P>
<P>
On legislation, Yam said the government would soon move a
resolution in the Legislative Council on an increase in the fixed
penalty for smoking vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
