<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian banking system, excluding the Central
Bank, had total deposits of 246.832 billion Egyptian pounds (71.98
billion U.S. dollars) by January 2000 against 246.071 billion
pounds (71.76 billion dollars) in December l999.
</P>
<P>
The monthly release issued by the Central bank's General
Administration for Economic Research showed that the total
government deposits in January hit 36.021 billion pounds (10.5
billion dollars) while non-government deposits reached 210.811
billion pounds (61.48 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Algeria's grain yield this season is expected to sink
to 2.1 million tons, the same as last season, according to a report
by Al-Haiyat.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Algerian officials, the report said that severe drought
had caused the drop in grain yield as the southern parts of the
country harvested nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
Official figures indicated Algerian grain output in 1998 hit 3.
25 million tons, then dropped to 2.1 million tons in 1999 due to
the lack of rain.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Algerian government resorted to foreign markets
to meet the local demand, spending 600-800 million dollars on grain
imports, according to Algerian Imports Supervision Bureau.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The World Bank offered to provide to the Egyptian
government a loan of 220 million dollars to finance a number of
infrastructure and education-oriented projects over 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Khalid Ikram, World Bank representative in Egypt,
Egyptian daily Al-Ahram said the proposed funding came within the
WB role in boosting Egyptian economic policies.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Finance Minister Medhat Hassaneen said the
present policy against foreign borrowing will be dropped to allow
the government to conclude a number of packages with foreign
funding institutions.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian daily Al-Wafd quoted the minister as saying that Egypt
would get 2 billion dollars in foreign loans during the coming
period, pointing out that the government had to pay a 11.5-percent
interest rate on internal debt whereas the foreign loans cost the
country just around 3.5 percent in loan service every year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- DuPont Co. of the United States and Sabanci Holding AS
of Turkey announced to build a new tire factory in South America,
reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by tire manufacturers DUSA Argentina
SA and DUSA Brazil SA in Buenos Aires, Argentina, earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
The DuPont-Sabanci joint venture will decide in the next 90 days
in which country, Argentina or Brazil, to build the new tire
factory beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey is listed as the second largest export
factoring country in the world after Japan, according to statistics
on the world factoring sector in 1999 published by Factors Chain
International (FCI).
</P>
<P>
More and more countries have come to use factoring because it is
a tool for enlargement, reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Factoring has increased by about 20 percent worldwide in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
