<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Demands AL Intervention to Halt U.S., British Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has informed the Arab League
(AL) of the recent bombings and airspace violations by the United
States and Britain, urging the pan-Arab forum to intervene to halt
such aggressions, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to AL Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid,
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz elaborated the bombings and
violations by U.S. and British planes on April 2-9, when the U.S.
and British jets carried out 166 armed sorties from their bases in
Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Aziz condemned these aggressions, stressing that they represent
a continuation of a "hostile trend" by the U.S. and Britain against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz urged the AL chief to intervene to help stop the continued
aggressive acts against Iraq, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
The AL has denounced the recent U.S. and British air raids
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on April 8, the AL said the air raids by
the U.S. and Britain against Iraq were carried out without the
authorization of the United Nations Security Council and therefore
were "unjustifiable" and "a flagrant violation" of the Iraqi
airspace.
</P>
<P>
On April 6, 14 civilians were killed and 19 others injured in
air raids by U.S. and British planes, representing one of the
heaviest casualties Iraq suffered since December 1998 when the U.S.
and Britain launched the four-night Operation Desert Fox air
strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The AL said it followed with deep concern the continued U.S. and
British air strikes against Iraq and called for an end to such
acts.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British aircrafts use bases in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait
to mount their patrols and bombings of the southern no-fly zone
which was set up after the 1991 Gulf War, with the so-called aim of
protecting the region's Shiite Muslims from possible attacks by
Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
A similar zone was imposed over northern Iraq claimedly to
protect the Kurdish community there.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has never recognized the no-fly zones, which are not
directly covered by any U.N. resolution and have been the sites of
almost daily skirmishes since the December 1998 air war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
