<HEADLINE> No Tension Across Line of Control: India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian Defense Minister George
Fernandes Friday allayed worries about the movement of Pakistani
troops along the Indo-Pakistani border in the western state of
Gujarat, saying it was "more of a defensive nature on the part of
Islamabad," the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes, who was in Calcutta to launch the Indian Navy's new
warship INS Brahmaputra, attributed the buildup of Pakistani
troops to two aspects: "One is more of a defensive nature on the
part of Pakistan and the other is perhaps related to the
Atlantique case now pending before the International Court of
Justice."
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani naval aircraft, Atlantique, was shot down by the
Indian Air Force when it allegedly strayed into Indian territory
last August. All 16 Pakistani Navy officers and crew aboard the
aircraft were killed, prompting Islamabad to file a 60 million U.S.
dollar compensation case at the international court.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister went on to say that there was no tension
along the Line of Control (LoC) in Kashmir, claiming: "There is
nothing to be worried about so far as the LoC is concerned, there
had not been any perceptible change in the LoC."
</P>
<P>
Asked if there was any possibility of further tension between
India and Pakistan in the Kargil sector of Jammu and Kashmir
during this summer, Fernandes said he had no such reports, the PTI
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
