<HEADLINE> Major Pak Infiltration Bid Foiled: India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian security forces foiled
on Friday a major attempt by Pakistan to send 60 heavily-armed
militants to the Kashmir valley, killing one of them and arresting
two others, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The infiltrators, allegedly backed by Pakistan, tried to sneak
into Indian territory through Nowgam area of Handwara in the
Kupwara sector in West Kashmir, but were confronted by alert
security personnel guarding the northern borders, the PTI quoted
official sources in Srinagar, capital of India-controlled Jammu
and Kashmir, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The militants were equipped with sophisticated weapons and the
exchange of fire lasted several hours, during which one
infiltrator was shot dead and two others nabbed, the sources said,
adding that the rest of the infiltrators fled back to Pakistan-
controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Indian security forces have launched a massive operation in
nearby forest areas to flush out infiltrators who could have taken
shelter in the dense woods, they said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first major infiltration attempt by Pakistan-
trained militants to sneak into the valley this season, the PTI
said, adding that chances of infiltration increase in summers as
snow starts melting on the mountain peaks on the Line of Control (
LoC).
</P>
<P>
The PTI also noted that with reports that more than 3,000
militants, including foreign mercenaries, were awaiting a chance
to intrude into Jammu and Kashmir to step up militancy, security
along the borders has already been beefed up.
</P>
<P>
Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes, however, said in
Calcutta Friday that he could see no tension along the LoC. "There
is nothing to be worried about so far as the LoC is concerned," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
