<HEADLINE> No Ugandan Cult Branches in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has denied the existence of branches of the Movement for the
Restoration of Ten Commandments of God, a cult which horrified
the neighboring Uganda by murdering some 1,000 innocent followers,
local media reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thorough investigation of all religious organizations in the
country has revealed that the cult, led by Joseph Kibwetere, did
not have any followers in Tanzania, the Minister for Home Affairs
Mohamed Seif Khatib told the Guardian newspaper on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said following the international warrant for the
arrest of Kibwetere and his conspirators issued by a Ugandan court
early this month, the Tanzanian government began investigating
whether the cult had a following in the country.
</P>
<P>
On March 17, a fire in the doomsday cult church in the
southwestern Ugandan village of Kanungu killed 530 people.
</P>
<P>
After the inferno, authorities unearthed a series of mass
graves in nearby villages, turning up about 400 corpses, many
strangled or stabbed.
</P>
<P>
The cult leaders who are said to have collected almost all the
money belonging to their believers are still at large. 
</P>
