<HEADLINE> Kenya to Export more Tea to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will soon command a larger
share of the Egyptian tea market owing to Egypt's entry to the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) last year
and the subsequent reduction of tariffs from 33 percent to three
percent.
</P>
<P>
The tariff reduction has made Kenyan tea more competitive,
forcing the Egyptian traders who used to import tea from Sri
Lanka, Indonesia and India to increasingly shift to Kenya for the
commodity, the East African Standard newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey released recently by the Tea Board of
Kenya, the upward market forecast will most likely be achieved by
October this year, when tariffs within the COMESA trading bloc
will be zero rated.
</P>
<P>
Kenya currently accounts for 80 percent of the tea import of
Egypt, which is Kenya's third largest market after the United
Kingdom and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The board said other than quality consideration, geographical
proximity to Egypt has been a boon to Kenyan tea exporters due to
the relatively low cost of shipment of tea from the country's
Mombasa Port to Port Said, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
