<HEADLINE> EU Joins Kenya, India in Opposing Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has promised
support for a return to a total ban on ivory trade proposed by
India and Kenya in the upcoming vote at the ongoing 11th
conference of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species held here from April 9 to 20.
</P>
<P>
Head of the EU delegation Christoph Bail told reporters on
Thursday that the EU "firmly believe the total ban on the
international trade in raw ivory should be maintained in the
interests of conserving elephants throughout Africa".
</P>
<P>
In the 10th conference of the convention in 1997, Botswana,
Zimbabwe and Namibia were allowed to export 59 tons of ivory to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and India have argued that the one-off sale of ivory to
Japan has caused increased poaching and stimulated illegal trade.
However, Botswana, Zimbabwe, Namibia and South Africa have asked
the conference to approve an annual export quota of ivory.
</P>
<P>
Bail said that it was too early to assess the impact of the
one-off sale by three southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU fully supported the CITES program on
Monitoring Illegal Killing of Elephants, which provides an
important mechanism for close monitoring of the elephants
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
