<HEADLINE> EU Welcomes Emission Reduction Promise by Japanese, S. Korean Car Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Friday welcomed commitments by Japanese and South Korean
automobile manufacturers to reduce passenger car carbon dioxide
emissions.
</P>
<P>
The commitments were made in line with recommendations adopted
by the European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, to the Japanese and South Korean automobile
manufacturing associations.
</P>
<P>
The commission recommended and the two Asian countries
committed themselves that the average fuel consumption of new
passenger cars will decrease an average of 2 percent by 2009, that
is converted to a reduction of carbon dioxide emission of 4 grams
per kilometer of driving compared with the 1995 level.
</P>
<P>
By 2009, all new cars sold in the European Union must meet an
emission target of 140 grams per kilometer of driving.
</P>
<P>
To meet the target, the fleet of new cars hitting EU roads will
have to consume less fuel, about 5.8 liters of petrol per 100
kilometers or 5.25 liters of diesel per 100 kilometers, a
reduction of 28 percent of fuel consumption as against the 1995
level.
</P>
<P>
Japan, South Korea and European car makers combine to represent
99.5 percent of the EU new car market.
</P>
<P>
Passenger cars contribute to about 12 percent of the EU's total
carbon dioxide emissions at the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
