<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: START II Ratification Victory For Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The ratification by the State Duma
on Friday of the START II treaty with the United States, which
sharply cuts the number of long-range nuclear weapons, represents
an initial victory for Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
The approval, which was passed by a vote of 288-131 with four
abstentions in the 450-seat lower house of parliament, also paved
the way for renewed negotiations on even deeper reductions and
marked a further thaw in Moscow's ties with the West.
</P>
<P>
Under the Treaty on the Further Reduction and Limitation of
Strategic Offensive Arms (START II), signed by former Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President George Bush on January
3, 1993, the two sides will each slash their stockpile of nuclear
warheads from about 6,000 to below 3,500 by the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate ratified the treaty in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Friday's ratification provided a boost for Putin before his May
7 inauguration and set the tone for his visit to Britain on Sunday
and a trip to the United States by Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
starting April 24.
</P>
<P>
It's the third time in recent years the treaty has come to the
Duma floor for ratification. It was pulled back twice at the last
minute because of U.S. military strikes, first against Iraq and
then against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Both the Kremlin and top government ministers have long called
for the approval of the treaty, arguing that it would get rid of
some of the country's aging nuclear warheads and concentrate
limited funds on new weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We've little room to maneuver," said Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev Thursday after a closed-door hearing at the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
"The reality is such that it is essential to ratify START II
and move on to START III," Sergeyev said, referring to a new stage
of the treaty that would cut each side's warheads to below 2,000
or even fewer.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Yeltsin and Clinton agreed at a summit in Helsinki
that START III would require the two countries' strategic nuclear
arsenals to be reduced to some 2,000 to 2,500 warheads. Two years
later, Russia proposed that START III require these arsenals to be
cut to some 1,000 to 1,500 warheads each.
</P>
<P>
Washington has yet to respond to Russia's 1999 proposal on
START III.
</P>
<P>
Russia's nuclear arsenal is already headed toward lower levels
because of dismantling and obsolescence, especially of the
submarines, airplanes and missiles that deliver the warheads. Some
estimated that at the end of the START II period in 2007, Russia
would have fewer than 1,000 warheads if current trends continue.
</P>
<P>
Friday's relatively easy passage of START II can also be
attributed to the weaker position of the Communist opposition in
the State Duma. Despite its status as the largest faction in the
house, it no longer commands the kind of majority that could
torpedo bills submitted by the ruling establishment.
</P>
<P>
Moscow also hopes that the ratification would help its standing
in dealing with U.S. attempts to change the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty, which are staunchly opposed by many countries
including Russia.
</P>
<P>
There are concerns that deep cuts into Russia's nuclear arsenal
will weaken the armed forces' ability to ensure so-called "
guaranteed destruction" if the United States decides to go ahead
with deployment of a powerful anti-ballistic missile defense.
</P>
<P>
"The strategic parity between Russia and the United States may
cease to exist if we implement START II and the United States
deploys its anti-ballistic missile defense," cautioned Ivan
Safranchuk, an expert with the Moscow-based Center for Policy
Studies.
</P>
<P>
To forestall such a scenario, the ratification bill Friday laid
down "extraordinary circumstances" under which Russia will
withdraw from the treaty "by way of exercising its state
sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
Putin told the deputies that if the United States undermines
the ABM treaty, Russia will pull out the entire system of
agreements with Washington on strategic nuclear forces as well as
START II and begin its own policy of nuclear deterrence.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1991 START I treaty, which is already being
implemented by the two countries, the number of warheads on
strategic missiles is to be cut to 6,000 each.
</P>
<P>
Russia currently has some 3,590 warheads on its land-based
ballistic missiles, 2,400 warheads on its sea-launch ballistic
missiles and another 552 warheads deployed on long-range missiles
that can be carried by the Air Force's strategic bombers,
Safranchuk said.
</P>
<P>
The ratification bill will now go to the Federation Council for
approval, before Putin signs it into law.
</P>
<P>
Yegor Stroyev, speaker of the upper house of parliament, said
the chamber may discuss the documents at its next session on April
19, the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
