<HEADLINE> EU Approves New Aid to Indonesia, Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Friday approved new humanitarian aid to Indonesia and Cambodia to
help refugees and people living in isolated places.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, granted 3.5 million euros (3.36 million U.S. dollars) for
East Timorese refugees now living in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian aid, to be channeled through the European
Community Humanitarian Office, will enable the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees and non-governmental organizations to
carry out relief work for the next six months.
</P>
<P>
The new aid brought EU humanitarian aid to Indonesia and East
Timor to 27 million euros (25.9 million dollars) since March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Another 8.5 million euros (8.16 million dollars) was approved
for a one-year program aiming at helping people living in isolated
parts of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The aid is to enable the International Red Cross, the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, the United Nations
Children's Fund and non-governmental organizations to carry out
relief work for the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
EU assistance to Cambodia since 1993 has amounted to 33.4
million euros (32 million dollars). 
</P>
