<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO's Medical Guidelines Win Wide Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A set of guidelines for
methodologies on research and evaluation of traditional medicine
drafted by the World Health Organization (WHO) won wide support
from doctors and government health officials worldwide, a senior
WHO official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officials and doctors attending a meeting here believed that
the guidelines are of great significance to the development of
traditional medicine of the members, Zhang Xiaorui, WHO's acting
coordinator of traditional medicine of the Essential Drugs and
Medicines Policy, told a media briefing.
</P>
<P>
WHO held a consultative meeting on methodologies on research
and evaluation of traditional medicine from April 11 to 14 in Hong
Kong. Over 80 officials and doctors from the WHO members and 30
WHO observers from all over the world took part in the discussion.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aimed to finalize a set of draft guidelines for
methodologies on research and evaluation of traditional medicine,
which will be an authoritative document for WHO member states for
reference purposes and will further facilitate traditional
medicine exchange at a global level, the WHO official said.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines will be published in September this year,
according to Zhang. "It is a set of internationally-recognized
standards, on which the member states can base their own policies
and regulations on traditional medicine, both the medicational and
non-medicational," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has set an example for WHO members with its five
years of efforts to formulate a set of standards and policies in
its drive to build Hong Kong into a traditional medicine port,
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Minister of Health Zhu Qingsheng also addressed
the opening ceremony of the four-day meeting, saying that China is
one of the countries which are rich in traditional medicine, and
the guidelines will help standardize the research and evaluation
of the traditional Chinese medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0142 </DOCNO>
