<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Share prices staged a rebound
in the afternoon on Singapore Stock Market Friday after spending
the morning in the red and rebounding later to offset the earlier
losses.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index gained 25.86 points to end at
2,189.76 points in active trading.
</P>
<P>
The total volume surged up to 371.39 million shares worth 834.
00 million Singapore dollars (488.38 million U.S. dollars).
Advancing issues outpaced decliners 260 to 77 with 193 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Hor Kew topped the volume list as it registered a turnover of
31.98 million units. ST Engg was the second most heavily-traded
stock with 15.95 million shares done. Wing T was the next with 15.
34 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SPH 100 topped gainers of the day climbing by 70 cents to end
at 32.60 Singapore dollars. CityDev and UOB gained 60 cents to
finish at 8.35 and 12.50 Singapore dollars respectively. DBS and
SPH went up 50 cents each to end at 23.50 and 32.50 Singapore
dollars separately.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 again led the descent of the day plunging by 190
cents to close at 43.60 Singapore dollars. Venture sank 130 cents
to finish at 21.10 Singapore dollars. PacCent slid by 100 cents to
end at 17.20 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that shares made slight headway at mid-day but
expanded big gains in the afternoon as switches out of electronics
stocks into bank and property shares prompted the key share index.
</P>
<P>
They said technology counters, like their counterparts
elsewhere in Asia, headed south, no thanks again to NASDAQ's
continued volatility.
</P>
<P>
However, brokers remained skeptical over the revival of "old
economy" stocks and their sustainability of gains due to the
sensitivity to interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
