<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indian Stocks Dance With Nasdaq  by Xiong Changyi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Dancing with the Nasdaq, the
Indian stock markets were gripped with nervousness as share prices
virtually collapsed on a fresh wave of all-round selling later
this week.
</P>
<P>
The 30-share Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) Sensitive Index
crashed by 254.69 points, or 4.69 percent to 5,172.13, wiping out
a whopping 424.29 billion rupees (9.87 billion U.S. dollars) off
the BSE's market capitalization, reducing it to 8,746.43 billion
rupees (203.41 billion dollars). Nearly 500 scrips, or 25 percent,
on the BSE hit the downward circuit breaker.
</P>
<P>
A depressed market also came under further pressure as
operators hammered down the Reliance Industries' scrip on account
of a buy-back offer that was much below market expectations. The
Reliance Industries decided to fix its buy-back price low at 303
rupees (7.05 dollars) per share Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the broader BSE National Index (100 scrips) lost 146
points, or 5.16 percent, to 2,820. Declines led advances by 1,289
to 563, meaning that every two out of three stocks lost ground.
</P>
<P>
With Wednesday's crash, the Nasdaq slumped by more than 750
points in the past four trading sessions, from a recent high of 4,
450 to 3,780, sending clear signals on the overvaluation of
technology and Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
Other major stock markets like London, Hong Kong, Taiwan and
Singapore too retreated sharply by 1.5 to 2 percent in the past
two days.
</P>
<P>
All over the world, analysts said, markets are a common
playground. If an investor or a mutual fund loses heavily at the
tech counters, then it will definitely try to book profits from
other sectoral stocks. It would be improper to isolate the Indian
markets from those in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Some fund managers said the broad trend remains positive but
the Indian bourses were waiting for the Nasdaq to stabilize. Since
most businesses have reported impressive results so far, the
markets could rebound sharply in the short run.
</P>
<P>
As Friday is a holiday in India, one dealer said that on Monday
the market will have to adjust itself to what happened on the
Nasdaq Thursday and Friday since a lot of investors still look to
the Nasdaq for directions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
