<HEADLINE> S. African Navy to Increase Its Role in African Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The South African Navy can
play an increasingly important role in peacekeeping missions and
crime prevention in Africa, Defense Minister Mosiuoa Lekota said
in Durban on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lekota said the navy is also likely to play a major role in
environmental management and protection, crime prevention, border
control and assisting in the event of natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
More specifically, the navy is expected to play a major role in
 combating illegal immigration and narcotics smuggling, he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing Africa as the "most conflict region today", Moeletsi
Mbeki of the South African Institute of International Affairs
said a decision by the South African government to allocate 30
billion rand (about five billion dollars) over the next few years
to acquire modern military technology.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said of the 30 billion (five billion dollars), 12 billion
(two billion dollars) will go toward acquiring four corvettes and
three submarines from Germany and the remainder will be used to
acquire equipment from countries such as Britain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The South African Navy currently has 24 ships and submarines,
of which 15 are commissioned at any given time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
