<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Issue on Whaling Dominates Wildlife Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sun Huixia
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The heated debate on whether to
relax the ban on commercial whaling or not has taken center stage
at the 11th conference of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) being held in Kenya's capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
An environmental group has hoisted a life-size whale balloon
outside the hall of the 11-day conference opened on April 9 to
protest at a proposal to partially lift the total ban on
commercial whaling.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Norway are making a bid to restart commercial whaling
by saying that three species of minke whales and a kind of gray
whale are abundant to be downlisted from Appendix I, which bans
any trade, to Appendix II, which allows limited trade.
</P>
<P>
The two countries submitted a similar proposal at the previous
 convention conference in June 1997, but fell only nine votes
short of victory.
</P>
<P>
Commercial whaling has been banned by the International Whaling
 Commission (IWC) since 1986, but whaling for scientific purpose
is still allowed.
</P>
<P>
Norway and Japan argued that there is no scientific basis to
continue the ban on minke and gray whales, since their populations
have returned to healthy levels, with an estimated of around
900,000 minke whales and about 20,000 gray whales.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservationists held that opening up the legal
trade in whale products means a disaster for whales since it gives
a huge incentive to poaching for the lucrative trade. They also
argued that poachers could use the legal trade as a cover.
</P>
<P>
Conservationists told delegates to the conference that DNA
analyses on whale meat in Tokyo markets have indicated that some
of it came from severely endangered species.
</P>
<P>
They said that unlike fish species, the whales are very
difficult to recover from the decline in the population. Whales
have a long gestation period and usually give birth only every one
or two years to a single calf and it takes many years for a baby
whale to reach sexual maturity.
</P>
<P>
Many species of great whales are still on the edge of
extinction. The population of blue whales of the Antarctic has
plummeted from 220,000 to just 460 due to overhunting, while the
number of the right whale has dropped from around 100,000 to
7,000.
</P>
<P>
"We are completely opposed to a resumption of whaling. There is
no immediate risk of extinction, but if there is a resumption of
commercial whaling, it could have a dramatic impact on numbers,"
said British Environment Minister Michael Meacher.
</P>
<P>
However, since the setback of the two whaling countries more
than two years ago, they have been involved in intense lobbying.
Some conservation groups accused Japan of offering aid to African
and Caribbean nations in exchange for their votes on whaling
issue.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Iceland are highly likely to back the proposal of
partially lifting the ban. Russia has objected the IWC's
moratorium and showed a strong interest in resuming. Iceland
recently joined CITES with reservation on 14 species of whales and
dolphins, including endangered blue whale.
</P>
<P>
A secret ballot is expected to be held in the next few days.
Observers here predicted that the vote would be close and it could
go either way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
