<HEADLINE> S. Korea's 76 Lawmakers-elect Suspected of Breaking Election Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Supreme Public
Prosecutor's Office said Friday it is investigating 76 of the
total 273 lawmakers-elect on charges of violating the election law
in Thursday's general election.
</P>
<P>
Among those who are suspected of having breached the law, 35
are from the ruling Millennium Democratic Party, 35 from the main
opposition Grand National Party while the minor opposition United
Liberal Democratic has three and three independents.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers-elect under investigation were all elected via
direct voting.
</P>
<P>
South Korean voters elected 227 legislators of the 273-member
unicameral parliament through direct voting. The rest 46 were
elected by the proportional representation system.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking into them because of earlier reports by the
National Election Commission or their rival candidates," said a
spokesman for the prosecutors' office.
</P>
<P>
The office has instructed district prosecutor's offices
nationwide to summon the suspected lawmakers-elect for questioning.
</P>
<P>
In Thursday's 16th election of the National Assembly, the main
opposition party won the largest number of seats, leading
President Kim Dae-jung's party by 18 seats, the National Election
Commission said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Grand National Party won 133 seats, against 115 for the
president's Millennium Democratic Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
