<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian State Duma Ratifies START-II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, lower
house of parliament, on Friday ratified the Russian-U.S. Strategic
Arms Reduction Treaty-II (START-II) by a vote of 288 against 131
with four abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact signed by Russia's ex-President Boris Yeltsin
and the former U.S. counterpart George Bush in 1993 in Moscow,
Russia and the United States agreed to cut the number of their
nuclear warheads from 6,000 to no more than 3,500 on each side by
2007. The U.S. Senate ratified the treaty in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The START-II will offer Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin
some leverage in arms control talks with Washington, which wants
to modify the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty to allow it
to deploy a national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
Duma deputies, voting for the treaty and two additional
statements on Friday, urged Washington not to violate the ABM
treaty and linked START-II weapons destruction to it.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats from the two countries said in Geneva on Thursday
that U.S. and Russian officials would hold talks next week to
assess the prospects for launching talks on START-III.
</P>
<P>
START-III was agreed in outline three years ago but the hard
work is to agree how deep the further cuts should be. Washington
is looking to cut arsenals to 2,000-2,500 warheads each, while
Russian officials say they are ready to go lower to 1,500 each,
again driven largely by economic considerations.
</P>
<P>
Friday, the Duma also passed several related documents,
including the September 1997 Russian-U.S. protocol prolonging the
term of the limitation of strategic offensive armaments from
January 1, 2003, to December 31, 2007.
</P>
<P>
The documents approved by the Duma shall be submitted to the
upper house of the Federal Assembly. Federation Council speaker
Yegor Stroyev said the upper house may discuss the treaty at its
next session on April 19.
</P>
<P>
The ratification bill enumerates the "extraordinary
circumstances" allowing Russia to withdraw from the treaty "by way
of exercising its state sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
These circumstances are: the violation of the treaty by the
United States capable of causing a threat to Russian national
security; the withdrawal of the United States from the 1972 ABM
treaty or the violation of the ABM treaty and related agreements;
a buildup of strategic offensive armaments by countries that are
not signatories to START-II in a way posing a threat to Russian
national security; the adoption and implementation by the U. S.,
other countries or alliances, including NATO such military
decisions that will create a threat to Russian national security,
including the deployment of nuclear arms in countries that joined
NATO after the signing of START-II; the deployment by the United
States, other countries or alliances of armaments obstructing the
operation of the Russian missile attack warning system.
</P>
<P>
The other extraordinary circumstances are emergencies,
including economic or technological emergencies, making it
impossible for Russia to implement START-II or capable of causing
a threat to Russia's environmental safety.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, in these and other extraordinary circumstances
"threatening the supreme interests" of Russia, the president "
shall take political, diplomatic and other steps to remove the
extraordinary circumstances or neutralize their consequences."
</P>
<P>
The bill says that the START-II treaty is going to be
implemented on the basis "of preserving the potential of the
Russian strategic nuclear force at a level necessary to guarantee
national security," "priority financing of the strategic nuclear
force" and "observation by the United States -- of the 1991 START-
I treaty."
</P>
<P>
In its turn the Russian government within three months of the
enforcement of the ratification law should draft and submit to the
president for approval a special federal program of limiting and
scrapping armaments and equipment of the strategic nuclear force.
</P>
</TEXT>
