<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Militant Sentenced to Death in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian Islamic radical has been
sentenced to death for leading a cell that killed three policemen,
three Coptic Christians and four other people in the past few
years, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Higher State Security Court handed down the sentence on
Thursday against Shaaban Abdel-Ghani Haridi, 30, but postponed
sentencing 13 other militants until May 10, said the pro-government
English-language paper.
</P>
<P>
The verdict will be transferred to the state mufti and chief
government cleric, Nasr Farid Wasel, for approval, which is a must
concerning a death sentence but largely a formality.
</P>
<P>
The 14 defendants were accused of belonging to an outlawed
terrorist group, believed to be al-Gama'a al-Islmiya (Islamic
Group), Egypt's most militant group, the pro-government paper said.
They were the survivors of a gang of 33, whose other 19 members
were killed by police.
</P>
<P>
They were also accused of attempting to kill four other
policemen and 14 civilians between August 1995 and April 1997 in
the southern governorates of Minya, Beni Suef and Fayoum as well as
robbing 114,000 U.S. dollars, gold and jewelry in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Islamic militants began in 1992 an armed campaign in an
attempt to topple the secular government and install a strict
Islamic rule. The insurrection has been crushed in a government
crackdown following the massacre of 58 foreign tourists by al-
Gama'a al-Islmiya in Luxor in November 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
