<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Govt Agrees to Reform Electoral Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government has
agreed to a proposal from the opposition to include reforms on the
Zanzibar Electoral Commission (ZEC) in a constitutional amendment
bill, newspapers reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Winding up the two-week long debate on the proposed Isles
constitutional changes on Thursday, Zanzibar Minister of State in
the Chief Minister's Office Iddi Pandu Hassan said the appointment
of members of the ZEC, including its chairman, will now have to be
approved by the 75-member House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
He said the move was in response to opposition legislators'
claim that they had no confidence in the commission because all
its members were appointed by the Zanzibar president.
</P>
<P>
However, Hassan made it clear that the Isles president would
continue to enjoy the prerogative in appointing ZEC chairman and
members.
</P>
<P>
The minister requested the House of Representatives to pass the
bill to allow the government to implement the Commonwealth
brokered peace accord signed in June 1999 between the ruling Chama
Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) party and the opposition Civic United Front
(CUF).
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, it was agreed that for free and fair
elections, the Zanzibar Electoral Commission should be reformed
before the general elections in October this year and members of
the ZEC will be appointed after a consensus is reached between the
two main parties.
</P>
<P>
The CCM party, led by President Salmin Amour, claimed a narrow
victory over the CUF in the 1995 elections, but CUF questioned the
result.
</P>
<P>
Political situation has become tense on the semi-autonomous
island in the Indian Ocean off mainland Tanzania after 18
opposition activists have been put in detention since December
1997 on sedition and treason charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Regionalism Remains Powerful in South Korean Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Regional loyalty or antagonism,
which determined South Korea's past elections, Thursday once again
proved its unbelievable strength in the country's 16th election of
National Assembly, or parliament.
</P>
<P>
Both the ruling Millennium Democratic Party (MDP) and the main
opposition Grand National Party (GNP) failed to win a needed
majority in the election.
</P>
<P>
Voters went to polls Thursday to elect 227 lawmakers of the 273-
member parliament, excluding 46 distributed to four parties in
proportion to voters.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 46 distributed seats, 21 went to the GNP, 19 to the
ruling MDP, five to minor opposition United Liberal Democrats (ULD)
and one to the Democratic People's Party (DPP).
</P>
<P>
The results of the direct election released by the National
Election Commission Friday showed the GNP has won 112 seats,
retaining its leading position in the unicameral parliament, while
President Kim Dae-jung's ruling MDP came in the second place with
96.
</P>
<P>
The ULD secured 12 seats, and other parties and independents
gained seven.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 112 directly-elected GNP legislators, 65 are from
Kyongsang region consisting of South and North provinces, Pusan
and Taegu which are GNP traditional political stronghold while 23
come from the Cholla area including South and North Choll
provinces and Kwangju which are ruling MDP's political base.
</P>
<P>
The ruling MDP could not gain a single constituency in
Kyongsang region while no candidate from GNP was elected in the
Cholla area although independent candidates gained four seats from
there.
</P>
<P>
However, the MDP's performance is better than expected although
it failed to win more seats than the GNP in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the announcement on inter-Korean summit, public pro-
stability sentiment and the civic groups' boycott campaign against
what they deemed "corrupt and incompetent candidates," the MDP
secured a greater majority in politically neutral Seoul, Kyonggi
province and Cheju island.
</P>
<P>
The MDP's failure to snatch the largest party position in
parliament is expected to remain an obstacle in the process of
President Kim Dae-jung's political and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Another surprising feature of the poll was a disaster for the
ULD, which lost its status as negotiating group on the floor, with
its number of seats dropping from 50 to 17 in its political hub
Chungchung zone as both MDP and GNP candidates did better than
expected there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the vote demonstrated growing public discontent and
cynicism to politics because a vote turnout stood at a mere 57.2
percent out of some 34 million eligible voters, the lowest in the
history of South Korean general elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
