<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- As authorities for a way to extend the detention of two
remaining Lebanese hostages, Barak Thursday accepted the
resignation of his POWs and MIAs Coordinator Ya'acov Perry.
</P>
<P>
The resignation followed Wednesday's Supreme Court and prison
authority's order to release 13 of the 15 Lebanese hostages being
held in an Israeli prison as bargaining chips for missing Israeli
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Perry, who served five years, said he felt he could no longer
properly carry out his job now that one of the main, "if not the
only," tool for retrieving the POWs and MIAs had been given up.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The government-imposed prohibition on new construction on the
Golan Heights has been lifted, the Prime Minister's Office Thursday
informed the head of the Golan Regional Council.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Thursday that the decision was only natural "when we
see only a very narrow crack left in the door of possible renewal
of the negotiations with Syria."
</P>
<P>
Barak added that the Golan projects had been held up for a few
months because of the prospects of talks with the Syrians, but
now "it is natural for them to be given approval to move forward."
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Retired Supreme Court Justice Zvi Tal Thursday presented to
Israeli Prime Minister and Defense Minister Ehud Barak the
recommendations of his nine-member committee on drafting yeshiva
religious students, a controversial topic between secular and
religious Israelis.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, those students would be allowed to
defer army service until age 23, when they could take a year off
the Torah study to decide whether to declare Torah as their trade
and stay in yeshiva or be drafted.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and French Defense Minister
Alain Richard Thursday signed a defense cooperation deal in which
Israel and France will invest in military research and development.
</P>
<P>
Richard arrived in Israel on Wednesday on a two-day visit, the
first by a French defense minister in three years.
</P>
<P>
He repeated France's policy that it will contribute troops to an
international force to guarantee security for Israel and Lebanon,
but only after an agreement between Israel and Syria, the major
power broker in Lebanon. 
</P>
