<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Remember Dark Days, Pray for Peace and Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 14 (Xinhua) -- April 13 is a day to be forever
commemorated in Lebanon's history. This day 25 years ago, a
devastating civil war broke out in this Mediterranean Middle East
country, to last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
On April 13, 1975, Christian militiamen ambushed a bus crowded
with Palestinians, kindling the 15-year sectarian war during which
150,000 were killed, 17,000 went missing and millions were turned
to refugees sheltering in other lands.
</P>
<P>
On April 13, 2000, thousands of Lebanese gathered in Martyr
Square in the Lebanese capital to commemorate the 15-year
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
Beirut, once dubbed "oriental Switzerland" and "mini Paris," was
turned into a showcase and proving ground of various weapons and a
paradise for snipers in the war.
</P>
<P>
Most of the buildings around Martyr Square are big banks
reconstructed after the civil war, standing in dazzling contrast
with a three-storey concrete frame with bullet holes in the facade.
A big hollow left by shell explosion stares the passers-by like a
dark eye, in mute testimony to what once occurred.
</P>
<P>
In the front of the parade were dozens of old women who were
holding pictures of their missing relatives in the war. A banner
preceded them that read "We have the right to know their fate."
</P>
<P>
The sixty-eight-year-old Zeinab Jabr was quivering and sobbing
as she held the picture of her eldest son Ibrahim Jabr who was
kidnapped on April 12, 1984.
</P>
<P>
"Tell me where is my son," she cried out, waving the picture.
</P>
<P>
Kidnapping was then a regular practice by belligerent militias
who were demanding the exchange of their captive colleagues or
simply asking for ransom. More than 500 people are still missing so
far, 10 years after the war ended.
</P>
<P>
Zeinab made her 13 other children emigrate after she lost her
Ibrahim. But she remained in Beirut herself, hoping against hope
that her son might come back one day.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of students followed in the parade, waving the national
cedar flags and calling "solidarity, peace, Lebanon the first."
</P>
<P>
Not having been in the battle-field themselves, these youngsters
are victims of the war as well. High unemployment that accompanied
the traumatized economy and spiraling inflation after the war have
forced many young Lebanese to find jobs in the oil-rich Gulf states
and other Arabic countries.
</P>
<P>
Youngsters and children are also easily falling victims to the
weapons that scattered in the community during the civil war. On
Wednesday, a college student who was playing a grenade in the
classroom was killed when the grenade exploded, also injuring his
six classmates.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the possibility of eruption of a fresh civil war,
Yagub Yasin, a taxi driver and a veteran of the civil war, replied
with dozens of "No."
</P>
<P>
"Lebanese have paid so much that none of us will forget those
dark days. We will not make any risk of igniting a civil war and
will not allow the occuring of a civil war," he said resolutely.
</P>
<P>
As the parade went on, more and more passers-by joined in,
sharing blue ribbons of the symbol of peace around their necks and
white flowers in hands.
</P>
<P>
With dusk fall, the minaret of the mosque near the square was
proclaiming the call for hierurgy as the bells of a rebuilt
Catholic church nearby tolled the hour, ringing for peace and
tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Gives Green Light for Gas Deal Talks With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian government has given
the green light for energy firms to negotiate the sale of natural
gas to Israel, after it blocked such talks for years amid tension
over the Middle East peace process, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by the Egyptian Ministry of Petroleum during a
visit by Israeli Minister of National Infrastructure Eli Suissa
came after Israel discovered its own gas fields.
</P>
<P>
The two sides "agreed to encourage gas companies in the two
countries to enter trade negotiations," said a statement issued
after a meeting on Thursday between Sameh Fahmi, Egypt's minister
of petroleum, and Suissa.
</P>
<P>
The statement released by the Egyptian Ministry of Petroleum has
cleared the way for natural gas suppliers working in Egypt's Nile
Delta, such as Amoco of the United States and Agip of Italy, to
sell gas to the Israel Electric Corporation.
</P>
<P>
"If such a deal is clinched, the two governments will work to
handle any matters pending between the two countries in order to
reach a full implementation" of the contract, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Suissa reportedly said in March that Israel would break off
contacts with Egypt over a possible deal to supply natural gas
following the discovery of gas fields off Israel's Mediterranean
coast. But he said here on Wednesday that the Jewish state was
still interested in diversifying its sources of natural gas despite
the recent discovery.
</P>
<P>
Israel had previously accused Egypt of foot-dragging on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
When tension increased with Israel while hardline Benjamin
Netanyahu was prime minister from 1996-1999, Egypt's former
minister of petroleum, Hamdi al-Banbi, pledged to the parliament
not to allow export of Egyptian gas to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Suissa wrapped up a three-day visit to Egypt on Thursday, during
which he also met with Egyptian Minister of Electricity and Energy
Ali el-Saeedi to discuss the option of future cooperation between
Israel and Egypt in the field of electricity.
</P>
<P>
El-Saeedi said after the talks that cooperation in the field of
electricity depends on the progress of the Arab-Israeli peace
negotiations, which are now in a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Three-quarters of Israel's energy consumption currently comes
from oil, most of the rest from coal and 4 percent from solar
energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
