<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Telstra Slashes Satellite Internet Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia's leading
telecommunications company Telstra Friday slashed the connection
cost for its satellite Internet service, dramatically reducing
barriers to high-speed Internet access to people in regional and
rural Australia.
</P>
<P>
The satellite service offers high-speed Internet access to
people unable to access Telstra's broad-band cable, which is only
available in the cities of Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
Until now the cost of the satellite service has been extremely
prohibitive, with the purchase and installation of the equipment
costing between 1,320 Australian dollars (818 U.S. dollars) and 2,
500 Australian dollars (1550 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Telstra Chief Executive Ziggy Switkowski said connection costs
would now be cut up to 80 percent, with purchase and installation
now priced at between 398 Australian dollars (247 U.S. dollars)
and 494 Australian dollars (306 U.S. dollars) for most parts of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Switkowski told a farmer conference on Friday that the biggest
savings would be in regional and remote Australia.
</P>
<P>
"For families with home computers, I want to make high-speed
Internet as affordable as a video or microwave oven," he said.
</P>
<P>
"For children in regional Australia I want to make it easier to
learn the skills needed to succeed in today's high-tech world,"
Switkowski said.
</P>
<P>
"For families in regional Australia I want to make it easier to
stay in touch with each other, the rest of the country and the
rest of the world," he added.
</P>
<P>
The National Farmers' Federation applauded the announcement,
which it said would now make services city people took for granted
available to those in rural and regional areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
