<HEADLINE> Manila Seeks Harsher Law vs. Overloaded Ship Owners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Following Wednesday night's
sinking of an overloaded vessel that killed at least 88 passengers,
Philippine authorities will push for a harsher law that makes
overloading a heinous crime, a senior official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Vicente Rivera of the Department of Transportation
and Communications said in a radio speech that this should compel
ship owners to toe the line and handcuff them from jeopardizing
passenger safety for the sake of profit.
</P>
<P>
"We must strengthen the law against overloading. We will push
to make it a heinous crime. Instead of mere reckless imprudence,
it should have a stiffer penalty. They are playing with human
lives here," Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
According to Friday's reports, the death toll has risen to 88
in the sea tragedy that happened Wednesday night when an
overloaded ferry sailing for Malaysia capsized off Jolo of the
southwestern island of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
"I am disgusted over what happened. This is a peak season for
overcrowding as students are on vacation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Many of our ship owners are undisciplined. That's the problem
with us," he said, adding that he has ordered the department's
legal bodies to draw up a draft measure.
</P>
<P>
As an effective effort to prevent vessels from overloading, the
secretary said his office would ask Congress to pass the proposed
measure immediately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
