<HEADLINE> Japan Welcomes DPRK's Bid to Join ASEAN Regional Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei
Kono on Friday welcomed a reported bid by the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) to join the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
"It is a major progress and we can call it a good situation. It
is a remarkable point," Kono told the Committee on Foreign Affairs
at the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
DPRK Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun has told his Thai
counterpart Surin Pitsuwan that the DPRK is "very keen" to join
the ARF, the Thai foreign minister said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) is the core
of the regional security forum, which has 22 participants, the 10
ASEAN members plus Australia, Canada, China, the European Union,
India, Japan, South Korea, Mongolia, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea,
Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Citing the DPRK's recent establishment of diplomatic relations
with Italy and agreement on the first-ever inter-Korean summit
slated for June,Kono said a major change is taking place
concerning Pyongyang's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
On the recent resumption of diplomatic normalization talks
between the DPRK and Japan, Kono said Pyongyang has shown a
sincere attitude and is eager for the realization of normalization.
</P>
<P>
"I feel a different atmosphere and I hope to have enough
discussion and achieve the goal in the negotiations through
perseverance," Kono said.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the DPRK began senior-level negotiations last
Wednesday in Pyongyang on establishing diplomatic ties, resuming
talks that collapsed in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed last Friday to hold the second round
of senior-level negotiations in late May in Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
