<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Army Signals Cut in Military Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's armed forces is currently
involved in contact with the foreign ministry to find ways in which
a reduction could be made in the country's military spending.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake on August 17 last year dealt a serious blow to
the country's economy, prompting the army to more rationally use
resources while maintaining its strength.
</P>
<P>
About 15 days ago, the Turkish general staff sent an official
letter to the foreign ministry, in which it requested that a study
be made of the declining military spending among Turkey's allies in
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is the only country in NATO increasing its military
expenditure. So we have to look to the possibilities of making some
cuts," said the letter.
</P>
<P>
It also requested a deeper evaluation of Turkey's immediate
neighbors, the number of which rose from eight to 10 after former
Soviet republics declared independence.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that despite the fact that Turkey's geopolitical
situation differs from many of its allies, dictating that Turkey
has higher military spending, there still exists the possibility of
seeking confidence-building measures with some of its neighbors,
which are inclined to be responsive to such an attempt.
</P>
<P>
Those neighbors that Turkey sees as having the potential to
improve ties are quoted as, to a certain extent, Syria in the south
and NATO ally Greece in the west.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has already been negotiating confidence-building measures
with the littoral states of the Black Sea such as Georgia,
Bulgaria, Romania, Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Bulgaria, which have already put mutual-confidence
measures in force in the 1990s, are negotiating to further this
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
It was reported, however, that Iran and Iraq in the southeast
and Armenia in the northeast are not at the moment perceived as
having the potential to improve ties with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A relative amelioration in the security environment in Turkey's
immediate periphery in the past year has raised cautious hopes in
the new century for Ankara to spend more energy on economic
recovery rather than busying itself with security issues.
</P>
<P>
This outlook, as some analysts argue, will lessen pressure on
the Turkish armed forces' efforts to meet its major arms
procurement and modernization programs.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense has continued to grab one of the major
sections of the pie in the 2000 fiscal year budget, despite a
slight drop in dollar terms compared to last year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense budget for 2000 is fixed at 7.6 billion
U.S. dollars, down from 7.8 billion dollars in 1999. But the
proportion of the defense budget to gross national product (GNP)
rose slightly to 3.3 percent from 3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The rise in the Turkish military expenditure has two causes.
Firstly, the demise of the Soviet Union brought Turkey to the
forefront of the world's most troubled regions, the Balkans, the
Caucasus and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
This strategic condition prompted the armed forces to increase
military spending as it has also assumed increased role in
multinational peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
The second reason for Turkey's slow process in establishing a
small but more mobile army with less money was fighting the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has been since 1984
struggling for an independent Kurdish state in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
Since joining NATO in 1952, Turkey has maintained the largest
standing army among European members of the alliance despite it was
poorly equipped.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important reasons cited for the military's
positive thinking toward finding ways of reducing military spending
was Turkey's acceptance by the European Union as a candidate member
during the EU summit in Helsinki in late December last year.
</P>
<P>
A few months ago, the Turkish general staff established EU
working groups to study the affects of the Helsinki decisions on
the Turkish military.
</P>
<P>
In its last two reports concerning the terms of Turkey's EU
membership, EU Commission has said that there has been a strong
military role within the Turkish political system.
</P>
<P>
The EU argues that this role of the military is one of the
obstacles in the face of Turkey securing full EU membership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
