<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's External Debt Triples in 18 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, Aril 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's external debt jumped
from 9.9 billion U.S. dollars in 1980 to 32.23 billion dollars in
1998, the Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) reported on Friday,
quoting figures released by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The country's long-term debt shot up from 8.5 billion dollars
in 1980 to 28.66 billion dollars in 1998. Public and publicly
guaranteed debt rose from 8.5 billion dollars in 1980 to 26.06
billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
World Bank and IDA (International Development Association)
loans and credits in 1980 stood at 1.15 billion dollars compared
with 6.93 billion dollars in 1998. Private non-guaranteed external
debt in 1980 was only 18 million dollars but in 1998 it had soared
to 2.6 billion dollars. In 1980, Pakistan's use of IMF (
International Monetary Fund) credit was 674 million dollars in
1980, and it rose to 1.36 billion dollars 18 years later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
