<HEADLINE> Australian Govt Asks Kosovar Refugees to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard and Immigration Minister Philip Ruddock Friday met a
representative of the Kosovar refugees in a last ditch attempt to
encourage those still in Australia to return home voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
About 30 of the remaining Kosovar refugees are refusing to
leave Australia now that the safe haven program has ended.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,000 Albanian Kosovars were brought to Australia at
the height of the conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Howard and Ruddock held talks with Albanian Kosovar
representative Eric Lloga to try to end the impasse.
</P>
<P>
Ruddock told reporters that the prime minister pointed out that
any change in policy now could set a precedent for other groups in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Ruddock said 90 of the remaining Kosovars had signed an
undertaking to leave Australia.
</P>
<P>
But those who refused to leave voluntarily by Sunday would be
considered to be in Australia illegally.
</P>
<P>
Lloga thanked Howard for listening to his plea but said the
government would not move.
</P>
<P>
"I appealed to the prime minister and the minister ... to allow
a moratorium for the Kosovars for a period of three months, during
which time any unexamined cases ... could be looked at," he said.
</P>
<P>
"After a lengthy discussion, which again the prime minister
kindly let us have, he felt he could not alter the position,"
Lloga added.
</P>
<P>
He said the process had now been exhausted and the refugees had
until Sunday to leave voluntarily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
