<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Great Lakes Nations to Meet for Goods Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is among the four countries
to meet next month to discuss the outcome of a study on
improvement of the transportation of goods in the Great Lakes
countries, Times of Zambia reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study on alternative transportation options for the Great
Lakes countries involving Zambia, Uganda, Angola and the
Democratic Republic of the Congo is an initiative of Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted COMESA director of infrastructure and
development Jerome Ntibarekerwa as saying in an interview in
Lusaka on Thursday that since the four countries depend on
transport routes to sea ports for their trade, there was need to
seriously look at the problems affecting the transportation
industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting would consider the study which will later
be submitted to donors for funding.
</P>
<P>
The study which had been finalized touched on the problems
hindering the effective transportation of goods between South
Africa and the Great Lakes region and proposes introducing railway
transport as the solution, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ntibarekerwa said: "Although road haulage of goods still takes
place, the deterioration of roads in most of the southern African
countries, makes the heavy haulage of goods by road almost an
impossibility."
</P>
<P>
He noted that since there was no major expenditure on
rehabilitation of road infrastructure, the deterioration will
continue, with tarmac roads changing into pot holed gravel roads.
</P>
<P>
The transportation of goods by sea from the ports in South
Africa and elsewhere to Dar es Salaam in Tanzania and Mombasa in
Kenya, used to be the preferred mode of transport in the past
because of the unreliable road and rail transport.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ports of Dar es Salaam and Mombasa have
however become unreliable because of congestion which has led to
massive delays of goods in the ports as well as pilferage and
damage.
</P>
<P>
He said plans were underway to privatize some of the activities
in the ports which would improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
"Although there are well-developed rail corridors running from
South Africa towards the Great Lakes region, there are some major
barriers which affect the effective transportation of goods," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
