<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt Urged to Speed Up Land Reform Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Cosmos Gonese, secretary general
of the Zimbabwe National Liberation War Veterans Association,
urged the government to come up with a concrete program that shows
its commitment to resettlement.
</P>
<P>
"If we withdraw from the farms, how long will it take the
government to implement orderly resettlement?" he raised the issue
on Thursday, adding that if there is no program showing
government's seriousness, then the black war veterans will stay on
the farms.
</P>
<P>
The former freedom fighters have occupied about 1,000
white-owned commercial farms since February to protest against
slow land redistribution.
</P>
<P>
The government on Thursday urged the war veterans to end farm
invasion since the parliament had approved a bill allowing the
government to seize white-owned farmland without compensation.
</P>
<P>
President of the Commercial Farmers' Union Tim Henwood
applauded the government's statement, saying, "This is a happy day
for our country."
</P>
<P>
President of the Zimbabwe Farmers' Union Silas Hungwe said,
"Indeed the war veterans must move out of the farms so that we
have orderly resettlement. Resettlement must be done in a proper
manner and not haphazardly." 
