<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Foreign Exchange Reserves Total $500 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's gross foreign exchange
reserves currently stand at 500 million U.S. dollars, covering
three-month import costs, according to a report from the newly
released weekly Business.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe Leonard Tsumba
dismissed market speculation that the country's foreign currency
reserves had fallen to dangerous levels of one day import cover.
</P>
<P>
However, he described the current foreign currency levels as
"undesirable". A country is said to have healthy foreign currency
reserves if the levels are more than three months import cover.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign currency reserves are expected to improve
when the tobacco-selling season opens towards the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
Tsumba said poor export performance had adversely affected the
supply of foreign exchange in the country.
</P>
<P>
"In this environment, financing critical external payment, such
as debt service, fuel, electricity and raw material imports, has
resulted in reduction of foreign exchange reserves to the present
undesirable low levels," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
