<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian State Duma to Ratify START-2 Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma, lower house
of parliament, will vote to ratify the 1993 Russian-U.S. Strategic
Arms Reduction Treaty-2 (START-II) and adopt two resolutions on
national defense and security at a closed session Friday, the
Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
spent Thursday briefing deputies in the 450-seat chamber and
appeared to have won more converts to a cause already backed by a
comfortable majority in the broadly pro-government Duma, seven
years after Washington and Moscow first agreed on the deal, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
At about 10 a.m. local time (0700 GMT) on Friday, deputies are
scheduled to meet for voting on the START-2, which would cut U.S.
and Russian nuclear warheads from 6,000 to no more than 3,500 on
each side by 2007. The U.S. Senate ratified the treaty in 1996.
</P>
<P>
With the pact passed, Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin
will boost his plan to improve Russian-West ties during his visit
to London on Sunday, also his first trip to the West as Russian
president.
</P>
<P>
The significance of that will not be lost on British and other
firms contemplating a safe return to greater investment in Russia.
It could also give a boost to arms control talks.
</P>
<P>
One of the resolutions, drafted by the Duma Committees for
International Affairs and Defense and to be approved Friday, sets
forth the lower house's position on cuts in strategic armaments
and on measures the Russian authorities should take in this area.
</P>
<P>
The draft urges Putin, in handling the issue of putting the
treaty into effect (the exchange of ratification instruments) "to
take into account the United States' plans and moves to create and
deploy a national missile defense system and the possibility of
that country's withdrawal from the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (
ABM) Treaty."
</P>
<P>
The Duma will call on the U.S. Congress and president "not to
initiate a new arms race, to reverse the plans to deploy a
national missile defense system and save the ABM Treaty." It has
voiced its support for the earliest possible beginning of talks on
START III.
</P>
<P>
The second draft deals with "ways of maintaining the combat
readiness of the Russian strategic nuclear forces and their
development."
</P>
<P>
The State Duma will urge Putin to ensure the unconditional
implementation of the federal law "on financing the state defense
order for the strategic nuclear forces," to draft measures on the
guaranteed supply of the Russian defense enterprises with energy
resources and to control and optimize prices on energy resources,
raw materials and components produced by monopoly-enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese President to Visit Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese President Tran Duc
Luong will pay an official visit to Mongolia on April 15-17 at the
invitation of his Mongolian counterpart Nachagyn Bagabandy.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on judicial cooperation between the two countries
will be signed during the visit, Vietnamese Ambassador to Mongolia
Nguen Te Dak said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We will pay more attention to the consolidation of the
traditional relations and cooperation between Vietnam and Mongolia,
especially in trade sectors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia established diplomatic relations with Vietnam on
November 17, 1954. In the following year, Ho Chi Minh, then head
of state of Vietnam, paid an official visit to Mongolia. 
