<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Japanese Imburses Chinese Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Katsuma Yasuko, an elderly
Japanese woman brought up in China by Chinese people during the
World War II, is now an enthusiastic supporter of China's Hope
Project.
</P>
<P>
The 75-year old Japanese woman came once again recently to
Weixian County, north China's Hebei Province, to see the 23
primary students under her financial help in the past five years
and donated 18,000 yuan (2,169 US dollars) and stationery worth 3,
500 yuan (422 US dollars) to them.
</P>
<P>
Yasuko began her support in 1995 by donating 10,000 yuan (about
1,205 U.S.dollars) to the Hope Project aiming at helping school
dropouts in poverty-stricken areas through social donation.
</P>
<P>
Since then, she has financially aided more than 40 poor
students in Yunnan, Shaanxi and Hebei Provinces.
</P>
<P>
Yasuko, with Chinese name Liu Jingzhen, separated from her
family during the Japanese invasion in China. She was brought up
by Chinese people and worked as an engineer in the China Film Data
Center until she returned to Japan to reunite with her family in
1979. She became a high-school Chinese teacher in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people's kindness and great care gave her unforgettable
impression, she said, making her decide to return the love by
offering financial support to Chinese children of poor rural
families.
</P>
<P>
Yasuko said that everyone in Japan should know what really
happened during the Japanese invasion in China during the World
War II. She told her students what she saw at that time. And she
started bringing some of her students to visit the Nanjing
Memorial Hall to the Massacre Victims since the year 1989.
</P>
<P>
Under her influence, many of her Japanese students have made
friends with Chinese students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Part-time Jobs Earn More Than Regular Sources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Some two out of every 100 income
earners in urban areas of China earn more from their part-time
jobs than from their regular sources of income, official figures
show.
</P>
<P>
According to the results of a nation-wide survey released by
the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) recently, part-time
workers account for 2.2 percent of the urban residents who have
regular sources of income. These people earn a monthly average of
661 yuan from part-time jobs, compared to 251 yuan from regular
sources of income.
</P>
<P>
One-third earn an average of over 500 yuan from part-time jobs
every month. Another half of them earn 200-500 yuan every month.
Only 2.5 percent of them earn a monthly income of more than 2,000
yuan from part-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly income of redundant workers in state-owned
enterprises is merely 74 yuan, which mainly comes from government
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers account for 39.2 percent of those who have
part-time jobs, while retirees account for 20.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government adopted a new employment policy in 1998
to encourage free flow of labor to ease unemployment pressure.
</P>
<P>
The government policy has prompted the workforce to change
their views on employment and helped more and more laid-off
workers to find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, China's urban unemployment rate
was 3.1 percent in 1999. The Chinese government predicts that the
figure will rise to 3.5 percent this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Tax Stimulates Consumption And Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since China began to levy income tax on interest earnings from
personal savings deposits on November 1, 1999, the revenue from
this tax has been growing for the past five months.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Ministry of Finance told Xinhua that
imposing the tax has not caused slumps in the amount of personal
savings deposits.
</P>
<P>
The country has reported steady growth in bank savings
deposits over the past two quarters except in December. In January,
the total amount of savings deposits jumped by 11 percent over the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Finance, in terms of proportions
in the total amount, time deposits are decreasing while current
deposits are increasing. People have already diverted part of
their savings to investment in securities and consumption.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the Chinese have greatly lowered expectations
on returns of savings deposits after the government repeatedly cut
interest rates and imposed tax on interest on bank accounts. They
are using a greater part of the surplus of income to invest in
stocks, bonds and consumption.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry official said that the results of
collecting the tax on interest earnings from bank savings deposits
were in conformity with the government goals. He predicts that the
tax revenue will continue to grow in the next nine months and meet
the government-set target by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shixian, an economist with the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, predicts that the government will collect about 20
billion yuan through the tax this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the tax will "help the poor" because 20 percent of
the Chinese population own 80 percent of the total savings
deposits.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has announced to use the interest tax
revenue to raise allowance to laid off workers, pensioners and the
indigent people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Making New Plan to Protect Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- China is making a new plan to
protect its water resources by strengthening regulation, the
Ministry of Water Resources said.
</P>
<P>
The new plan will divide rivers and lakes into different
categories and setting targets for the protection of water
resources.
</P>
<P>
China will strive to improve the quality of water by curbing
contamination and ceasing overuse of underground water, according
to the plan.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, the ministry implemented rules for water
resources protection. However, mounting pressures brought about by
water shortage and pollution in the wake of rapid economic growth
has prompted the government to implement new rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
