<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Chinese Cities Report Dusty Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of cities in
northern China this week reported dusty weather, the China
Environmental Monitoring Center said today in its weekly Air
Quality Report.
</P>
<P>
Dry weather, high-temperatures, a lack of vegetation in the
region, and strong winds were blamed for dusty weather resulting
in a drastic increase of suspended air-borne particles in the air
in northern China.
</P>
<P>
From April 7 to 13, the eight cities of Tianjin, Beijing,
Xining, Shijiangzhuang, Yinchuan, Qinghuangdao, Hohhot and Taiyuan,
reported hazardous air, while Zhengzhou and Lanzhou reported poor
air.
</P>
<P>
Urumqi, Harbin, Xi'an, Shenyang, Chongqing, Changchun,
Nanchang, Jinan, Yantai and Lianyungang reported slight air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Twenty cities including Guangzhou, Shanghai, Changsha,
Hangzhou, Chengdu, enjoyed fairly good air, while Zhanjiang,
Haikou, Beihai, Zhuhai, Shenzhen, and Guilin reported excellent
air.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, Beijing Xining and other 35 cities listed suspended
particles as the major pollutant. Sulfur dioxide was the major
pollutant in Chongqing, Changsha and Guiyang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
