<HEADLINE> 4 Million Kenyan Kids Involved in Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Over four million Kenyan children
aged between six and 16 might be involved in child labor,
Permanent Secretary of Kenya's Human Resource Development Ministry
Kang'ethe Gitu has said.
</P>
<P>
Gitu made the revelation in a written speech read at the
opening of a child labor workshop here on Thursday, saying the
rise of child labor in the country is attributed to inadequate
legislation, poverty, HIV/AIDS and a breakdown of family
structures.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper on Friday quoted Gitu as
saying the child labors, accounting for 41 percent of the
country's children population, are working in environment that are
dangerous to their development and physical well-being.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Ministry of Education, Science and Technology to
put more emphasis on non-formal education for the sake of
disadvantaged children, adding the education system should be made
more relevant and affordable in order to check the high dropout
rate.
</P>
<P>
Jane Ong'olo, national coordinator of an international program
on elimination of child labor, told the meeting that "250 million
children around the world suffer such exploitation, and we know
that 120 million of them work full time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
