<HEADLINE> Kenya to Host Joint Peace-keeping Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 4,000 soldiers from
Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania and the United States will begin joint
military exercises at Kenya's coast next week to train regional
forces in peace-keeping operations, the state-owned Kenya Times
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, code-named Natural Fire 2000, will start on April
21 and end on May 27, and also involve forces from European
nations and observation contingents from South Africa, Belgium,
Britain, the Organization of Africa Unity and the East African
Community.
</P>
<P>
The coalition force involves 2,000 Kenya soldiers, 300 troops
from Tanzania and 200 from Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Julius Sunkuli, minister in the Office of the President, said
here on Thursday that the purpose of the exercise is to train the
regional forces in the planning and execution of peace support
operations in a joint and combined setting.
</P>
<P>
During the exercises, the forces will be taught skills for
coordinating a multi-faceted peace-keeping operations including
conflict operation and resolution, disaster relief and
humanitarian assistance programs, Sunkuli added. 
</P>
