WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Rasheed Wallace scored 27
points to lead the Portland Trail Blazers to a 93-77 victory
Thursday night over San Antonio Spurs as Tim Duncan watched from
the sidelines, out with a cartilage tear in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
Without Duncan, the Spurs were neither effective on offense nor
intimidating on defense.
</P>
<P>
The Trail Blazers shot 56.5 percent from the field for the game,
a season high for a Spurs opponent, and led by 16 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
In Chicago, Washington Wizards edged Bulls 109-103. Richard
Hamilton collected a career-high 26 points, including 11 of
Washington's last 13 points.
</P>
<P>
The loss spoiled an outstanding night for rookie Elton Brand,
who scored a career-high 44 points and grabbed 12 rebounds in
becoming the first Bull to score 40 points since Jordan had 44 on
April 18,1998.
</P>
<P>
Brand's previous career high was 38 on February 24 at Indiana.
</P>
<P>
Jordan wasn't at the United Center for the Wizards' first game
in Chicago since he became a part-owner and president of
basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
In Houston, Rockets defeated Dallas Mavericks 111-102. Steve
Francis scored 16 points, 11 rebounds and had seven assists to
lead Houston to its fifth straight win, the longest current streak
in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
Walt Williams led Houston with 21 points. Cuttino Mobley
contributed 20 points and Moochie Norris 19 for the Rockets, who
have won nine of 12.
</P>
<P>
Michael Finley had 35 points for Dallas, which had won five in
a row.
</P>
<P>
Charles Barkley, who retired after rupturing a left leg tendon
in December, announced he plans to play in Houston's final game,
Wednesday at home against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
In Sacramento, California, Kings had a 130-107 victory over
Golden State Warriors. Chris Webber scored 22 points and Vlade
Divac had 15 points.
</P>
<P>
Sacramento, seventh in the Western Conference standings,
increased its lead over idle eighth-place Seattle to one game with
four remaining.
</P>
<P>
Larry Hughes had 35 points and 12 rebounds for Golden State,
which had won two in a row. 
</P>
</TEXT>
