<HEADLINE> Container Shipping Service Connects Central China Province With World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
Communications has granted the city of Changsha in central China's
Hunan Province the right to operate international container
shipping services.
</P>
<P>
Now, cargo from Changsha destined for export can be directly
loaded onto containers after being inspected by local customs, and
the containers can be reloaded onto foreign ships via Shanghai,
said an official with the Changsha Port Administration.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, this practice will eliminate five
intermediate steps and will shorten the time needed to export
cargo from Changsha by half a month, while saving 100 US dollars
for each standard container compared with previous methods.
</P>
<P>
Changsha, the capital of Hunan and the home province of late
Chinese leader Mao Zedong, is situated on the Xiangjiang River, a
tributary of the mighty Yangtze River, and boasts a fleet of 40
container ships capable of carrying 6.8 million deadweight tons.
Seventy-five percent of Hunan's exports are accomplished via
Changsha's inland river port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
