<HEADLINE> South African Ambassador Confident of Sino-South African Ties (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said he will go home soon to help with the final
preparations to ensure the complete success of President Jiang's
state visit to his country, and that the visit will bring benefit
to the people of both countries.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, four agreements are expected to be signed,
namely agreements on culture, science and technology, agriculture,
avoidance of double taxation and police cooperation, according to
the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and China should work together to achieve all the
objectives set by the two presidents, he said, adding that there
still exists enormous potential for bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the good cooperation in coal mining between the two
countries and direct friendly links between some regions of the
two nations, he said that South Africa, which has expertise and
has now begun to produce high-tech mining equipment, is planning a
program to ink an agreement with China for expanding bilateral in
the mining sector.
</P>
<P>
Increased cooperation can be pursued by establishing joint
ventures and exchanging expertise and technical know-hows in
related areas, he said. China is welcome to be involved in other
mineral resources in South Africa. Agreements will be signed to
strengthen contacts at provincial and city levels.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that even an ordinary Chinese farmer could have a
friend in South Africa," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
