<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Scientists Discuss Environmental Issues in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 Chinese and foreign
scientists attended a symposium of the Scientific Committee on
Problem of Environment (SCOPE) under the International Council of
Scientific Unions (ICSU), today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that SCOPE have ever held a seminar in
China. The theme of the symposium is promoting eco-development in
developing regions.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day meeting, environmental scientists from
nearly 30 countries will discuss common environmental problems and
will advise governments on environmental policies.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Guangzhao, vice-chairman of China's National People's
Congress (NPC) Standing Committee and president of China
Association for Science and Technology, said at today's opening
ceremony that while science and technology have made rapid
development, serious environmental problems have destroyed
significant parts of rainforests, eroded billions of tons of top
soil each year, increased production of greenhouse gases by
burning more coal and oil, released a huge amount of poisonous
waste and left hundreds and thousands of people in poverty.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope for strengthening mutual understanding
and cooperation between Chinese scientists and their colleagues
from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
SCOPE was created by the tenth meeting of the Executive
Committee of ICSU in 1969. Its current scientific programs focus
on sustainability, managing social and natural resources and eco-
system processes and biodiversity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
