<HEADLINE> Australia to Study Gulf War Veterans' Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The health of Australia's Gulf
War veterans will be studied to help the defence force treat the
health of personnel sent overseas in the future, a senior
government official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study will compare the health of the veterans with that of
defence personnel who did not take part in the conflict, Veterans
Affairs Minister Bruce Scott said.
</P>
<P>
Almost 2,000 personnel involved in the conflict will be listed
on a nominal roll as the first stage of the study, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The nominal roll will form the basis of a study to compare the
health of Gulf War veterans with that of Australian Defense Force
personnel who did not participate in those operations," Scott said.
</P>
<P>
A tender process to select a research team to conduct the study
is being finalized and data collection is expected to take about
six months.
</P>
<P>
Scott said he expected to receive the report early in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visitor Arrivals in Philippines Down 0.6 Pct in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Visitor arrivals in the
Philippines declined by 0.6 percent in January this year to 188,
752 from 189,798 in the same period last year, the government said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Records from the Department of Tourism showed that the drop was
due largely to a decline in arrivals from top tourist markets,
particularly the United States, Taiwan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
While previously posting an upgrowth, the records showed a
turnaround as the number of incoming American guests dropped 5.3
percent to 38,260 from 40,414 last year.
</P>
<P>
From the previous No.3 spot, Taiwanese fell to fifth place with
a total of 8,292 travelers, 47 percent less than last year's 15,
806, due mainly to the Philippine-Taiwan airline dispute.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hong Kong registered a total of 10,362 travelers for
the period, 14 percent lower than the 12,058 recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
Japan and South Korea continued to boost visitor arrivals by
posting growth in the first month of the year.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the second largest travel market, posted a visitor
arrival of 37,592 while South Korea remained a flourishing tourist
market as the number of visitors from that country hit 17,914 for
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
