<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Fuel Supplies Improve Gradually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The fuel supply situation in
Zimbabwe has improved gradually this week, with queues shortening
at most filling stations in central Harare by Thursday, the daily
Herald reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some service stations have stopped rationing diesel and petrol,
as supplies begin to stabilize.
</P>
<P>
Paraffin rationing continued Thursday at five to 10 litres per
customer at service stations.
</P>
<P>
The President's Office has reported that all the fuel tanks at
 Mozambican central port city of Beira are full. The tanks are
holding 16,278 million litres of petrol and 6,024 million litres
of diesel from kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"Effort is being made to ensure that there will be no fuel
shortages during the Easter holiday," said Munyaradzi Hwengwere,
spokesman for the fuel task force in the President's Office.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the country was now receiving 80
percent of its normal daily fuel consumption.
</P>
<P>
The oil industry reported that imports were arriving daily, but
 improvement will be gradual rather than immediate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
