<HEADLINE> COMESA Gets $100 Million Loan From World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has mobilized 100 million U.S. dollars
from the World Bank to be given out as development loans to member
states, according to COMESA Clearing House consultant Mahmood
Mansour.
</P>
<P>
And plans to establish an investment agency are underway,
Mansour said in an interview in Lusaka on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Times of Zambia newspaper quoted Mansour as saying
that another 100 million dollars would come from the Africa
Development Bank, the European Union and the European Investment
Bank for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
COMESA was in the process of creating an African Trade
Insurance Agency (ATIA) to guarantee security of investments
flowing into the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mansour said all countries that were eligible to borrow under
the International Development Agency (IDA), a World Bank wing,
would be able to obtain loans from the 200 million dollars
facility.
</P>
<P>
He said that 40 countries would be targeted to get loans that
would enhance economic growth on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"The loans will vary between 15 million dollars for countries
with smaller economies and 25 million dollars for those with
either medium or bigger economies," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
