<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silicon Valley-Based Sun Microsystems Reports Profit up 49 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Sun Microsystems, networking
computer products maker in Silicon Valley, Thursday reported 49
percent growth in profits for the fiscal third-quarter as its
revenue, earnings, and bookings growth hit record levels.
</P>
<P>
Sun, which has been increasing its market share in a rivalry
with Hewlett Packard Co., said it enjoyed its highest quarterly
profit margins, on an operating basis, in 15 years, according to
reports from the company.
</P>
<P>
Sun reported a third-quarter profit of 436.2 million U.S.
dollars, excluding one-time items, up 49 percent from last year's
291.9 million dollars. With gains from the sale of equity
investments and other one-time items, net income for the latest
quarter totaled 508.1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sun's revenue rose to 4.005 billion dollars, a 35-percent
increase from the third quarter of 1999. Order bookings rose by a
record 41 percent over last year's third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say Sun is best known for its enterprise
servers that use the Solaris operating environment, workstations,
storage products, UltraSparc microprocessors, and the Java and
Jini platforms.
</P>
<P>
Java is a programming language often used to provide animation,
calculators, and other functions on Web pages. Jini technology is
designed to connect a variety of devices to a network and enable
them to work together.
</P>
<P>
The analysts say that Sun has benefited strongly from the
growth of the Internet, since its servers, microprocessors, and
programming languages are commonly used by companies to build and
run their Web sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
