<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank and Hong Kong Help Education In North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Donations from the World Bank (WB)
and Run Run Shaw, a well-known entrepreneur in Hong Kong, have
greatly improved education in poverty-stricken areas in north
China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The first donation 18.266 million U.S. dollars by the World
Bank has been allocated to twenty counties in building more than
two million sq. m of schools, buying more books for reading rooms
and desks and chairs for students.
</P>
<P>
The WB's second donation of 13 million U.S. dollars together
with 11.71 million U.S. dollars from the Chinese government has
given to eleven cities, 18 poor counties, and 11 normal schools to
carry out the nine-year compulsory education programs and to
improve the quality of teaching. .
</P>
<P>
The six donations by Shaw totaling 37.25 million Hong Kong
dollars have been used to set up 20 middle schools, 31 primary
schools and to rebuild a college in the province.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi, a province with some 40 poverty-stricken counties, is
one of the main places in the country to carry out the anti-
poverty project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Following are the cultural news
highlights released by Xinhua from April 7 to 13:
</P>
<P>
-- CASS to Construct Advanced Computer Network
</P>
<P>
President of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) Li
Tieying visited the Legend Group on April 7, seeking technological
help from the computer giant for the academy's computer network
construction.
</P>
<P>
China must push ahead with the computerization of scientific
information, said Li, also a member of the Political Bureau of the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee. Researchers can no
longer use primitive methods for social scientific studies when
high-technology prevails.
</P>
<P>
-- Chengjiang Fossils to Apply for World Heritage
</P>
<P>
China plans to apply for UNESCO's World Natural Heritage
listing for the arthropod fossil stratum site located in
Chengjiang county in southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Chengjiang fossils, dating back some 500 million years, include
large quantities of tiny multicellular animals and their embryos,
which are said to be the earliest multicellular animals on Earth.
Their discovery has led to significant breakthroughs in attempts
to understand human evolution.
</P>
<P>
-- China to Promote Cultural Prosperity: Outlook Weekly
</P>
<P>
China's Minister of Culture Sun Jiazheng said that the state is
determined to raise the overall quality of cultural products and
improve management of the cultural industry in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Sun said in the latest issue of Outlook Weekly which hit
newsstands on April 10 China plans to speed up the construction of
symbolic cultural buildings, such as a proposed national museum, a
giant national theater and other high-level museums in the near
future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Computer Network Readingrooms to be Set Up Across China
</P>
<P>
The National Library of China will establish computer network
readingrooms across the country, a development expected to extend
the library into every corner of China.
</P>
<P>
Forty million pages containing tens of thousands of books held
by the National Library of China will be able to be read without
limits of space or time.
</P>
<P>
-- 5,000-Year-Old Ruins Discovered in East China
</P>
<P>
Two 5,000-year-old sites belonging to the Liangzhu Culture have
been discovered in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
A score of Chinese archeologists gathered at Dakan Village,
near Jiangyin City, on April 6-8 for investigations into the sites.
Some 13 imperial tombs of the Liangzhu Culture, one of the sources
of the Chinese civilization, were unearthed at the two sites. Over
235 items of jade, pottery and stone ware were unearthed from the
tombs. The No. 13 tomb is the largest of its kind ever found in
China.
</P>
<P>
-- China Compiles Biography for Outstanding Scientists
</P>
<P>
A series of biographies of thousands of noted Chinese
scientists is being compiled by the China Association for Science
and Technology (CAST).
</P>
<P>
More than 1,320 scientists who have made great contributions to
China from 1840 to 1920 have been included in the 29-volume book.
</P>
<P>
-- Danish Modern Design Art Show Opens in Guangzhou
</P>
<P>
An exhibition of modern architecture and design art of Denmark
opened on April 10 in Guangzhou, capital of south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, entitled "the Danish Wave", commemorates the
50th anniversary of diplomatic ties between Denmark and China. On
display are more than 70 pieces highlighting Denmark's
contemporary construction styles and designing arts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Cultural Corridor To Be Built At Three Gorges
</P>
<P>
A cultural corridor will be built along the Three Gorges of the
Yangtze River within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The 193-km-long Three Gorges, in an area between Chongqing
Municipality and central China's Hubei Province, is a well-known
scenic spot in China. The area holds 1,282 archeological sites
including ancient tombs, unique bridges and famous stone carvings.
The most brilliant sites comprise a 2.8 billion-year-old rock and
1.4 million-year-old paleoanthropological ruins.
</P>
<P>
-- China to Host Int'l Singing Contest
</P>
<P>
China will host a major international vocal music contest from
November 8-17 in this capital of Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The ten-day event, the first of its kind in China, is aimed to
promote exchanges between music circles and develop the art of
vocal music, according to an official with the Ministry of Culture.
</P>
<P>
-- China's Biggest CD Production Center Established
</P>
<P>
The Hangzhou Natural (Group) Company, a leading optical
technology enterprise in Hangzhou, capital of east China's
Zhejiang Province, has become the country' s largest CD (compact
disc) production center.
</P>
<P>
The company now produces 30 million recordable CDs annually,
according to the company source. Production lines and technology
are imported from Sweden and Germany. The company aims to have an
annual production capacity of 100 million discs.
</P>
<P>
-- Palace Museum Adds 240,000 Relics to its Collection in Half
Century
</P>
<P>
The Palace Museum has added more than 240,000 treasured relics
to its collection since the founding of the People's Republic of
China in 1949, according to a recently published data book.
</P>
<P>
The book provides readers with specific information on as many
as 240,888 items, most of which were donated by governmental
organs. The State Administration of Cultural Heritage (SACH) gave
101,772 relics to the museum and another 21,875 were donated by
individuals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
