<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Researchers Find Protein in Yeast Regulating Cell Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A group of scientists at
Seattle's Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center have found that
humans and yeast share a protein that appears to play a key role
in regulating cell growth.
</P>
<P>
The world-renowned research institute said Thursday that the
protein, called Rrn3, may play a pivotal role in the chain of
events that determines how fast cells grow.
</P>
<P>
"For a protein to be fundamentally conserved from yeast all the
way up to humans implies there must be a reason that it has been
preserved from an evolutionary standpoint," the institute quoted
Ronald Reeder, head of the group, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We know that if you don't have this protein, you don't grow.
Even if there are other mechanisms that human cells use to
regulate cell growth, the fact that this one is so well conserved
in humans means it's an important piece of the puzzle in our
understanding of growth control," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
While the researchers are primarily excited about this
fundamental new understanding of the molecular mechanisms that
trigger cell growth, the institute said, the discovery that Rrn3
functions in humans as well as yeast may have several long-range
benefits.
</P>
<P>
According to the institute, this regulatory molecule may be a
unique drug target, since disabling it might halt the growth of
cancer cells. The protein also might be used as a biomarker to
develop highly sensitive cancer-screening methods, as the activity
of Rrn3 is expected to mirror the rate of cell growth throughout
the body.
</P>
<P>
The researchers believe the protein appears to be a key player
in an as-of-yet unidentified cell-signaling pathway that results
in cell growth. Rrn3 may act as the "on" switch that instructs
ribonucleic acid (RNA) polymerase I, the enzyme responsible for
reading the genetic code, to pump out lots of ribosomal RNA, which
is part of the cellular workbench that makes the proteins
necessary for cell growth. The more ribosomal RNA produced, the
faster the cell grows.
</P>
<P>
Understanding how this pathway works in the growth of yeast
will be crucial to unlocking the mystery of the process in humans,
the institute said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Gateway Company Reports Sharp Growth in Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Gateway Inc., the No. 2 U.S.
direct seller of personal computers, posted a 37-percent income
growth for the first quarter, said the company on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
San Diego-based Gateway said its net income rose to 136 million
U.S. dollars, compared with 99.5 million dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Sales climbed to 2.34 billion dollars in the three months ended
March 31 from 2.1 billion dollars a year earlier. Computer
shipments rose 16 percent to 1.3 million units from 1.1 million
units.
</P>
<P>
During the quarter, Gateway and its Internet partner, America
Online Inc. added a net 300,000 subscribers to their Web access
service.
</P>
<P>
Gateway showed strong growth overseas, led by its Europe,
Middle East and Africa unit, which posted a 31-percent revenue
growth than a year earlier. Britain and the Netherlands were
particularly strong, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Revenues from the Asia-Pacific region rose 27 percent than a
year ago, despite a slow start to the quarter, the company said.
It cited strong sales in Japan and a sharp up-tick in southern
Asia, including Hong Kong, Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Gateway said its non-PC income exceeded 25 percent of overall
income in the first quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
