<HEADLINE> Agassi Retires with Injured Hamstrings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- World No. 1 Andre Agassi of
the United States injured his right hamstring Thursday night and
retired in a match against Jiri Vanke of the Czech Republic at the
Atlanta Tennis challenge tournament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Agassi was leading 2-0 when he felt a tightness in the right
hamstring but suffered the pull in the ninth game as he served at
4-4, 15-40. Agassi ran down a lob by Vanek and returned it with a
shot between his legs.
</P>
<P>
Agassi said he felt a sharp pain as he chased down the
following shot into his backhand corner.
</P>
<P>
The injury makes Agassi doubtful for the first Tennis Masters
Series in Europe next week in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
Three American seeds -- No. 4 Michael Chang, No. 5 Chris
Woodruff and No. 7 Jeff Tarango entered the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Chang edged Julian Alonso of Spain 7-5, 6-7, 6-3. Chang next
takes on Woodruff, a 4-6, 6-2, 6-2 winner over Australian Todd
Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
