<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Rural Communities Set Up to Cut Poverty:  CP Executive  by Yang Qingchuan, Huang Yong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 14 (Xinhua) -- By developing several rural
communities in the poor regions of Thailand during the recent 20
years, Charoen Pokpand Group Corporation (CP Group), one of
Thailand's top companies, has helped hundreds of landless farmers
shake off poverty, a senior executive of the company declared
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua News Agency, Abhaichon
Vacharasinthu, the assistant vice president of CP Group, explained
how the company managed to effectively set up certain rural
communities to relieve poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said,"We devised the village community plan 20 years ago and
set five basic objectives."
</P>
<P>
"First, raise year-round income for the farmers on a continuing
basis. Second, improve the farmers' quality of life. Third, create
job and vocations in the rural areas. Fourth, ease the problems
arising from migrating labor into urban areas. Fifth, strengthen
the community and the family institution," Abhaichon said.
</P>
<P>
The first rural community which CP chose to conduct its poverty-
relieving plan is Nuang Hua village in the poverty-stricken areas
of Cha Choeng Sao Province, about 100 kilometers east of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Abhaichon said, it is a rural community created by 50
destitute landless farmers with financial, technological and
commercial support from CP Group .
</P>
<P>
"In collaboration with the public sector and financial
institutions, CP undertook the support activities for Nuang Hua
village in a full-integrated manner," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Abhaichon said that with CP Group as their financial guarantee
and loans from banks, each of the 50 farmers of Nuang Hua village
bought a piece of land of 25 rais (4 hectares), with 20 rais (3.6
hectares) of which used for production, while the rest for housing.
</P>
<P>
"Under CP Group's development plan, the 20 rais' land for
production are divided into different vocational sections as rice
farming, rice milling, vegetable farming, fruits and flowers
planting, livestock raising and fishing. Thus the farmer can have
diversified income sources," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abhaichon noted that as a business giant covering many
industrial and technological sectors, CP Group does have the "
special ability" to help those farmers. He said, "our support
came in the forms of investment, seeds, animals, fertilizer,
pesticides, vaccine, academic and technology know-how as well as
purchase of produce, price guarantee and marketing services."
</P>
<P>
During the past 20 years, the incomes per capita in Nuang Hua
have grown continuously, now at 30,000 bahts (780 US dollars)
monthly, nearly four times of the average income standard of the
whole country.
</P>
<P>
"However, having more money does not mean real improvement,"
Abhaichon said, "we realized that the farmers should have modern
community life and social abilities."
</P>
<P>
He recalled that in 1987, for expanding rural community plan,
CP Group and many public and private sectors of Thailand jointly
set up the Rural Lives Development Foundation, which focuses on
human resource development of the rural communities in those
impoverished regions.
</P>
<P>
As Abhaichon introduced, the foundation now offers five courses
on "leadership development" a year with 25 young farmers a year to
a course, totaling 125 trainees per year. The trainees are chosen
from three "pilot village community" from 96 villages in the
backward northeastern region of the country.
</P>
<P>
When asked about how extensive the community plan would be,
Abhaichon said: "critics have said that the number of communities
was so limited and may seem unhelpful to the vast poor areas
around the country. However, we should be patient."
</P>
<P>
He said,"if those areas proved to be a good model, and we will
introduce them to other places."
</P>
<P>
Explaining the motive of the company to carry out rural plan,
Abhaichon said," not every big firm is willing to help poor people.
"
</P>
<P>
Abhaichon said, "so if we decided to do this, we should first
have the sincerity, and secondly, we need cooperators. Finally, we
should make government and the poor understand our plan. Helping
poor people make money is good, but the more important thing is to
teach them how to use and to reserve money."
</P>
<P>
As for the question about the company's profit in the community
plan," he said, "successful rural communities are the potential
business partners in the future, and will set a model for
relieving the country's vast, poor regions."  
</P>
</TEXT>
