<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes Zimbabwe Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain Thursday welcomed a
Zimbabwean High Court ruling that police must take action to clear
the illegal occupation of white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement that the
ruling was in Zimbabwe's own interests that land reforms are
carried out in an orderly and transparent way.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's High Court Thursday dismissed a police application
to overturn an earlier eviction order on thousands of veterans of
the country's 1970s liberation struggle.
</P>
<P>
That means the supporters of President Robert Mugabe, who
seized white-owned farms, would be cleared out from the farms.
Zimbabwe police had argued earlier that order was impossible to
enforce without risking civil war.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome that decision. It is in Zimbabwe's own interests
that land reform is carried out in an orderly and transparent way,
which does not ride roughshod over the rights of individuals,"
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the police will now begin to carry out this order
and that calm will return to the farms of Zimbabwe," the foreign
secretary added. 
</P>
