<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Development for China's Western Region (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Urban development will greatly help the reallocation of surplus
rural labor caused by these policies, and urbanization is also the
best way to relieve the pressure on natural resources while the
massive campaign to develop the west is carried out.
</P>
<P>
The western regions' current under-population and backward
infrastructure is unfavorable to industrial development, but
urbanization can optimize the configuration of resources and the
labor force.
</P>
<P>
China's western regions should accelerate the construction of
small- and middle-sized towns and combine small cities, as far as
possible, into groups of medium sized cities.
</P>
<P>
The populations in unlivable areas should be encouraged to move
to towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
The western region must devote itself to developing modern and
comprehensive cities instead of specialized ones.
</P>
<P>
Also, the guidelines for traffic systems should give prominence
to key urban projects.
</P>
<P>
Attention also should be given to the improvement of the cities
' electricity and gas and water supply systems, as well as
communications, traffic facility construction, and all kinds of
service enterprises to improve the cities' investment environments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Development for China's Western Region (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The key to China's western
development strategy is to develop a group of modern cities in the
region, according to a signed article on the China Economic Times.
</P>
<P>
The article on the Beijing-based newspaper notes that in 1998,
44 percent of China's gross domestic product (GDP) was produced by
the country's 231 above-county-level cities, which shows the
importance of cities in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
However, all the country's five most important economic centers,
Shanghai, Beijing, Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Tianjin, each with GDP
exceeding 100 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars), are located in
the east. And among 45 cities, each with GDP over 20 billion yuan
(2.41 billion US dollars), only seven are located in the western
region.
</P>
<P>
In the last 20 years, China's eastern region has developed a
group of small- and middle-sized new cities around major cities to
form a regional economic network.
</P>
<P>
The early 1980s' reforms of the rural economic system, and the
1990s' campaign to boost border trade with Russia, western Asia
and southeast Asia, gave priority to the west.
</P>
<P>
However, the western region has not taken full advantage of
these policies to form a series of central cities that could bring
along the entire region's economic development.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of 2000, Chinese government adopted two new
policies for stopping cutting trees, and turning farmland back to
forests, lakes and grasslands in order to protect the ecology
environment in the western regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Capital Free of Leaded Gasoline Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We are committed Jakarta will be free of unleaded gasoline in
2001 and hopefully it will be followed up in other regions across
the country," the minister was quoted by the Antara News Agency
Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the "Blue Sky" environmental program would be applied
across Java island in 2002 and across the country in 2003.
</P>
<P>
Keraf said he was optimistic that the program in Jakarta would
be successful because the state-owned oil company Pertamina's
refinery plant in Balongan, West Java, had the capacity to supply
the unleaded gasoline for the city.
</P>
<P>
To supply other regions, the minister said, Pertamina would
still need large investment for establishing refinery plants.
</P>
<P>
Lead is used to increase the octane number of gasoline to lower
its burning point and make it easier to burn. Lead poisoning may
cause upper respiratory tract infections, increase blood pressure,
cause heart attacks and damage kidneys.
</P>
<P>
While many countries had successfully ended the use of lead in
gasoline, Indonesia was still home to a large amount of the
hazardous substance.
</P>
<P>
Despite the many campaigns of nongovernmental organizations to
end the use of leaded gasoline, the Indonesian government has
delayed its own deadline for Pertamina to stop producing leaded
gasoline from last December to 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
