<HEADLINE> Brazil Expects Peruvian Elections to Help Strengthen Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government
expressed its hope Thursday that the Peruvian elections will help
strengthen democracy in the country and in the whole hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the Brazilian Foreign Ministry Thursday
afternoon said that the Brazilian government believes the second
round of the elections would be more transparency.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Brazilian government has been closely
following the election process and has been regularly informed
about the development by the Elections Observation Mission of the
Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
Official results on Sunday's vote show of the 97.68 percent
votes counted, President Alberto Fujimori had 49.84 percent, his
major rival 40.31 percent and other candidates gained the rest.
Election officials said the remaining ballots could not
fundamentally change the tally to give Fujimori the majority
needed to avoid a runoff.
</P>
<P>
A runoff election will be scheduled for late May or early June.
</P>
