<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four European States Uncover International Drug-Smuggling Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The police in Hungary, Britain,
Germany and Austria have collaborated to expose and capture two
individuals reportedly members of an international drug-smuggling
ring.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Hungarian anti-organized crime group told
a news conference Thursday that Hungarian police arrested two
Bulgarian men in a hotel in Szolnok State. The authorities say
they also confiscated two billion forint (7.55 million U.S.
dollars), and 30 kilograms of heroin, about 80 percent pure.
</P>
<P>
After joint investigations by the four European countries, the
two drug-traffickers are believed to be members of an
international drug-smuggling group. They were reportedly in
charge of trafficking drugs from Turkey to London via central and
eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of the criminal group is believed to be in
Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Drug-smuggling is becoming increasingly rapacious throughout
the world. Hungary, situated in central Europe, has become a main
drug-trafficking channel. Last year, Hungary seized 153 kilograms
of heroin. The country has confiscated an equal amount of heroin
in the first quarter of this year, exceeding the entire total of
heroin confiscated last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
