<HEADLINE> Motorola To Increase Investments in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Motorola Company, a global
leader in providing integrated communication, decided to increase
its investment for Brazil this year in view of the rapid growth of
the country's cellular telephone market.
</P>
<P>
Robert Gowney, the multinational firms' operations director
said Thursday that Motorola will invest 60 million U.S. dollars
this year to expand the production of cell telephones in its
Jaguiariuna plant in the state of Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
The volume of investments for Brazil could increase even more,
depending on the business evolution, added Gowney, who is in Rio
de Janeiro attending a meeting of the company council.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. company invested 150 million dollars in Brazil during
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
Motorola wants to conquer, according to Gowney, a bigger slice
of the contracts for infrastructure supply to meet the demand of
cell telephones for the C band, for which bidding will be opened
later this year.
</P>
<P>
Motorola sales in Brazil reached 950 million dollars in 1999,
and its target for this year is 1.3 billion to 1.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
An investigation made by IBOPE shows that Motorola leads the
Brazilian cell telephone market with 30 percent of the market.
</P>
