<HEADLINE> Dominican Republic Denounces International Banking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Dominican Republic President Jaime
Fernandez Mirabal condemned international organizations here
Thursday for the harsh conditions their assistance imposes on poor
countries.
</P>
<P>
"They impose terms on us," said Fernandez during the panel of "
Summits, Compromises and Cooperation," part of the Group-77 Summit.
"Many times we have no other option but to give up something which
affects our sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
He accused international entities of financing poor countries,
of exceeding their authority, often instructing the benefactors on
how to use the funds, without considering the government's opinion.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned another problem regarding the veteran technicians
sent by the entities, claiming the salaries they receive are
higher than those of ministers in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez also discussed discrepancies between the World Health
Organization and the Inter-American Development Bank, which is
reluctant to fund developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"That, of course, causes extraordinary distortions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These are the challenges we have to face," added Fernandez,
who opposes the general practice of "accepting help as if it were
charity".  
</P>
</TEXT>
