<HEADLINE> Japan's Lawmakers Lash Out at Ishihara's Anti-Foreigner Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Legislators of Japan's opposition
parties Thursday lashed out at Tokyo Governor Shintaro Ishihara
for derogatory remarks made about foreigners over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
During a session of the House of Councilors' Committee on
Foreign Affairs and Defense, Michio Sato of the Niin Club-
Jiyurengo bloc urged Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei Kono to
demand that Ishihara apologize for his remarks and retract them.
</P>
<P>
"I will think about it," Kono replied, adding, "They are
inappropriate remarks, and I feel the are quite regrettable."
</P>
<P>
Hideo Den of the Social Democratic Party said the government
should review its plan to hold a joint disaster drill in September
between the Self-Defense Forces and the Tokyo metropolitan
government.
</P>
<P>
At a session of the House of Representatives Security Committee,
Ishihara was also blasted.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Ishihara told a ceremony of the Ground Self-Defense
Force, "Atrocious crimes have been committed again and again by
sangokujin and other foreigners who have illegally entered Japan.
We can expect them to riot in the event of a disastrous earthquake.
"
</P>
<P>
"Sangokujin" is a Japanese term that literally means "people
from third countries." Referring to people from former Japanese
colonies in Taiwan and the Korean Peninsula, as well as their
descendants, the term gained currency after World War II. It is
now widely regarded as a derogatory term.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara came under fire from various fields, including
Japanese government officials, opposition parties and the South
Korean government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
