<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Map Three Human Chromosomes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists have mapped
the gene maps of three human chromosomes, Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The three pairs of chromosomes, numbered 5, 16 and 19,
containing 10,000 and 15,000 genes, which account for about 11
percent of a human's whole genetic material.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the department's Joint Genome Institute at Walnut
Creek, California, documented the sequence of nearly all the
chemical building blocks of the chromosomes, Richardson said at a
policy conference of American Association for Advanced Science.
</P>
<P>
The genetic information on the three chromosomes may give clues
to some cancers, diabetics and other diseases, Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
And these information will be available to private and public
researchers free of charge.
</P>
<P>
In November 1999, scientists in Britain, the United States and
Japan announced they had mapped the gene draft of chromosome 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
