<HEADLINE> Toronto Stock Exchange Downed for Fourth Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada's main stock index Thursday
closed below 9,000 points for the first time since February 3 in
its fourth consecutive day of decline.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto Stock Exchange 300 composite index (TSE 300), which
broke the 10,000-point plateau two weeks ago, lost 82.26 points to
8,965.41.
</P>
<P>
Volume was 185.7 million shares traded worth 4.28 billion
Canadian dollars (about 2.91 billion U.S. dollars), compared with
the previous day's volume of 172.64 million shares worth 4.82
billion Canadian dollars (about 3.30 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
TSE 300 wiped out all the midday rebound after jittery
investors once again fled technology stocks in fear of
overvaluation of the high-flying technology sector, where such
tech stars as Microsoft, Motorola and Canada's Research in Motion
Ltd. (RIM) were recently estimated to have flat earnings.
</P>
<P>
Notel Networks and BCE Inc, which together account for 30
percent of Toronto's stock market, finished off 6.00 Canadian
dollars (about 4.08 U.S. dollars) at 146.00 dollars (about 99.18 U.
S. dollars) and 3.50 Canadian dollars (about 2.38 U.S. dollars) at
152.50 dollars (about 103.59 U.S. dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Among other technology losers were Sierra Wireless, which fell
12.00 Canadian dollars (about 8.15 U.S. dollars) to 77.00 dollars
(about 52.31 U.S. dollars); Certicom Corp., which dropped 11.75
Canadian dollars (about 7.98 U.S. dollars) to 82.25 dollars (about
55.87 U.S. dollars); and JDS Uniphase, which slipped 6.10 Canadian
dollars (about 4.14 U.S. dollars) to 134.40 dollars (about 91.30 U.
S. dollars
</P>
<P>
TSE 300's fourth day of decline came in abreast with the
technology heavy Nasdaq composite index, which lost 2.46 percent,
or 92.85 points, at 3676.78 at its close Thursday, when bellwether
stocks and computer-chip makers turned negative to drag Nasdaq
deeper into bear territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
