<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Capital Moves to Attract Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The historical town of Luoyang in
central China will make efforts to protect cultural relics and
develop infrastructure to attract tourists, China Daily reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Located in Henan Province, Luoyang boasts a history of nearly 5,
000 years. Archaeologists have confirmed that Luoyang was the
capital during the reign of 96 emperors in 13 dynasties over a
period of 1,529 years.
</P>
<P>
It has seven major historical and cultural sites under state
protection, 53 under province protection and over 800 under
municipal and county protection.
</P>
<P>
The Longmen Grottoes, the White Horse Temple, the tomb of
Emperor Guangwu of the Han Dynasty (206 B.C. - A.D. 220) are among
the attractions.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city received 76,000 overseas tourists and four
million domestic tourists.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Luoyang has taken advantage of its peony culture
to promote tourism. With a cultivation history of more than 1,500
years, the city has over 600 varieties of peony.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the Luoyang peony fair is held annually to draw
millions of Chinese and foreign tourists for sightseeing and trade
talks.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve tourism services, the city has accelerated
infrastructure construction. At present, 19 projects with a total
investment of 3.5 billion yuan (about 421 million US dollars) have
been launched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
