<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China City Ambitious About Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 14 (Xinhua)-- Chongqing, a municipality in
Southwest China, plans to invest 60 billion yuan on highway
construction in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The investment is an increase of 17 billion yuan over what was
originally planned three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Peng Jiankang, deputy director of the city bureau of
communications, said that the city is building six expressways
which will link the city with existing expressways from Shanghai,
Chengdu and Baotou.
</P>
<P>
Currently, it takes three days from Chongqing to drive to
Beihai, a coastal city in the South China Sea. When the highway
project is completed in 2005, the trip will take only eight hours,
said Peng.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the city has spent 17.5 billion yuan
on building 1,800 km of highways. The total length of highways in
the city expanded from 1,200 km three years ago to 280,000 km.
</P>
</TEXT>
