<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Use of Banned Ammunition Incurs Radiation Contamination in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav government Thursday
accused the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) of violating
international war and humanitarian norms by using depleted uranium
ammunition during its final airstrikes on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It cited a survey report as saying that the Western military
bloc had employed the internationally banned ammunition during its
March-June operation in Kosovo in a quantity 10 times more than
used elsewhere, which has created severe environmental problems in
the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The report, based on tests on a variety of samples collected,
was conducted by Yugoslav researchers. They pointed out that the
radiation contamination in "some samples was 1,000 times above the
level that jeopardizes the population and the environment."
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav government said it has taken every possible step
it could to reduce the radiation impact on the environment, while
providing physical examination services and medical treatments to
those Kosovo residents exposed to the radiation.
</P>
<P>
A German news agency, DPA, reported Wednesday that NATO
admitted using armor-piercing uranium depleted ammunition against
Yugoslav tanks in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
