<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe President Denounces Interventionist Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe,
speaking before the South Summit here Thursday, faced up to "neo-
colonialist powers" and denounced the "intervention and unilateral
application of sanctions against countries that do not abide by
their desires."
</P>
<P>
He mentioned as a typical example the threat now pending over
Zimbabwe for effecting an agrarian reform that puts in the hands
of the peasants of Zimbabwe some 5 million hectares of fertile
farmland now in the possession of former British white settlers.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the colonialists appealed to the European Union
and the Bretton Woods institutions to force Zimbabwe to give up
its policy and have threatened to apply economic sanctions against
it, thus "taking us down the road of confrontation."
</P>
<P>
Britain and Zimbabwe have been at loggerheads since Zimbabwe
backed veterans of the country's 1970s liberation struggle. The
veterans seized white-owned farms and urged Britain, the colonial
power, to pay the white settlers for their seized land. Britain
has refused Zimbabwe's demands.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said unilateral sanctions applied by international
powers and international financial institutions are in flagrant
violation of the United Nations Charter and the sovereign rights
of the states.
</P>
<P>
These imperialist and colonialist trends must be stopped, said
the Zimbabwe president, adding that "bilateral questions cannot be
resolved with gangster-like methods."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe condemned these interventions by military powers and has
called on the Group of 77 member countries to support the
declaration of the Non-Aligned Movement approved in the recent
ministerial meeting of Cartagena, Colombia, in favor of the
national sovereignty and self-determination of the people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
