<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Used-car Market Gets Guidance From New Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Used-car buyers can feel a little
bit more secure about their purchases, thanks to a recent Chinese
Government action.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor and Social Security recently released a
set of plans demanding appraisers of second-hand vehicles to earn
professional certification.
</P>
<P>
The circular, to be implemented July 1, is expected to improve
appraisers' techniques and regulate the used-car market, today's
China Daily quoted the ministry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
It also provides legal documentation to put in place a new
labor system that demands workers have professional certificates,
the source said.
</P>
<P>
According to ministry statistics, used vehicles have an annual
trading volume of 18 billion yuan (2.17 U.S. dollars). The
expanding market now sees 800,000 second-hand vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
"It requires professional staff and scientific means to make
proper evaluations of used vehicles," said Li Boguang, who works
with the National Automobile Renewal Office.
</P>
<P>
Since last fall, the ministry and the State Administration of
Internal Trade have organized training programs and exams for
appraisers working on used cars.
</P>
<P>
Training has proven effective in regulating the market,
cracking down on illegal trade and preventing smuggled and
rejected automobiles from being sold again, Li said.
</P>
<P>
As for appraisers working in auctioning, pawn brokerage,
insurance and other industries, the two governmental departments
will provide training programs beginning in April.
</P>
<P>
Those working without professional certificates will be
investigated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
