<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Approves Republican Budget for Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Republicans pushed a final
budget of 1.83 trillion U.S. dollars for next year through U.S.
Congress Thursday that calls for tax cuts, debt reduction and more
money for the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
On a pair of near party-line votes, the House voted 220-208 to
approve the Republican-written budget for fiscal 2001 which starts
on October 1, 2000, and the Senate followed suit by 50-48.
</P>
<P>
The measure approved Thursday was a House-Senate compromise of
similar budgets each chamber had passed earlier.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton needs not to sign the measure, but an
election-year veto battle looms over 13 annual spending bills and
any tax legislation lawmakers send him translating their budget's
plans into reality.
</P>
<P>
The package leaves the Republicans and Democrats poised for a
campaign season touting starkly different views of how to use
surpluses from the non-Social Security side of the budget.
Republicans would use much of it for tax cuts, Democrats prefer
more domestic spending and debt reduction, and each accuses the
other of jeopardizing Social Security surpluses they have pledged
to leave alone.
</P>
<P>
Both sides would use the 1 trillion dollars in expected Social
Security surpluses over the next five years to reduce the 3.6-
trillion-dollar publicly held debt, with the goal of eliminating
it by 2013. The rest of the 5.7-trillion-dollar national debt is
money the government owes Social Security and other federal trust
funds.
</P>
<P>
Most economists say such a dramatic reduction of the publicly
held debt would press interest rates downward and fuel the economy.
</P>
<P>
But the two parties are divided over how to use the surplus
projected from the rest of the budget.
</P>
<P>
Republicans would use much of it for a tax cut of at least 150
billion dollars and perhaps more than 200 billion dollars,
depending on lawmakers' decisions and how much economic growth
occurs over the next few months. Democrats want a smaller tax
reduction, with more money set aside for domestic programs and
debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
The Republican budget would set aside up to 40 billion dollars
over five years for any new prescription drug benefits that
lawmakers add to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
Both parties say they want to enact a prescription program this
year. Clinton wants it to cover all elderly Americans, while
Republicans want to limit it to lower-income people or those with
extremely high drug bills.
</P>
<P>
The budget also calls for 311 billion dollars for defense next
year, 5 billion dollars more than Clinton wants. And it would
spend 289 billion dollars for domestic programs, about 30 billion
dollars less than Clinton seeks.
</P>
<P>
The remaining two-thirds of the budget covers interest payments
on the debt, plus benefits like Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
