<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Demands Safety Review after Zonta Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Formula one driver Michael
Schumacher has demanded urgent safety improvements to Silverstone
after seeing a fellow driver sent flying at the spot of his own
horror smash.
</P>
<P>
The German wants changes before next week's British Grand Prix
at the Northamptonshire circuit after Ricardo Zonta was launched
over a safety fence by a tyre barrier.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian was sent rolling along the gravel at Stowe Corner,
where Schumacher broke his leg last year, after the right-front
wheel of his British American Racing car ripped off at 300kmph
along Hangar Straight.
</P>
<P>
Zonta hit the tip of the tyre barrier, went airborne over an
eight-foot high fence and wall before landing upside-down in a
grassed no-go area.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old amazingly was able to walk away from the crash
with just a cut finger, though BAR called off testing while they
carried out an urgent review of why the front push-rod on the car'
s suspension failed.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher, who began testing at the track for the first time
since breaking his leg after crashing his Ferrari into a tyre
barrier, was one of the first drivers at the scene.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old also watched videos of the incident and
immediately revealed the Grand Prix Drivers' Association will be
contacting the sport's safety officer, Charlie Whiting, to call
for improvements.
</P>
<P>
"We can be very, very lucky that Ricardo is almost unhurt which
shows how good car safety is right now," said Schumacher, who
missed seven races after his accident last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
