<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rugby League Legend Edwards Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- British rugby league legend Shaun
Edwards has announced his retirement after a glorious 17-year
career.
</P>
<P>
He was the most decorated player in the game's history but has
had to retire due to injury.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old former Wigan and Great Britain half-back said a
succession of knee and head injuries had led him to hang up his
boots.
</P>
<P>
Edwards played in the first four games of the season with his
latest club, London Broncos, before being sidelined with a
hamstring strain and has decided to take a complete break from the
game.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Rugby league has given me so much and I would like to
thank everyone who has helped me throughout my career,
particularly the tremendously loyal fans who have provided me with
so many fond memories."
</P>
<P>
Edwards' announcement comes on the eve of the Broncos' Super
League match against Wigan, the club with whom he enjoyed so much
success.
</P>
<P>
He made 467 appearances, scoring 274 tries, in 14 trophy-filled
seasons for Wigan from 1983-97 and played in 11 Challenge Cup
finals at Wembley, most recently with London 11 months ago.
</P>
<P>
London's former Wigan coach John Monie said: "I don't think
British rugby league will ever again see a player who has achieved
what Shaun has. His career has been a feat of remarkable endurance
and his contribution to the game has been immeasurable."
</P>
<P>
"He has battled with injury of late and I think this is the
right decision. I wish him well and I'm sure he will be of great
service in the area of coaching some day if that is what he
chooses to do," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
