<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chelsea and Wise Fined by FA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Chelsea have been fined 50,000
pounds for failing to control their players during a clash with
Wimbledon in February.
</P>
<P>
Captain Dennis Wise was fined 7,500 after pleading guilty to
insulting behavior in preference to a charge of misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The Blues were censured and slapped with the fine plus costs at
a Football Association disciplinary hearing in London on Thursday,
despite a plea of not guilty to misconduct.
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon right-back Kenny Cunningham and Dons coach Mick
Harford were also at the hearing, which was adjourned until a
later date.
</P>
<P>
It could be a number of weeks before a decision is reached in
the case of the Wimbledon players charged.
</P>
<P>
The charges relate to a fracas in the tunnel after the London
derby on 12 February. The FA said there had been a prolonged
confrontation between players and club officials outside the
Chelsea changing room that lasted about three minutes.
</P>
<P>
It began when Wise and Cunningham became involved in a row in
front of referee Peter Jones moments before the final whistle, and
had to be separated by officials.
</P>
<P>
The referee is understood to have witnessed the incident from
start to finish.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea managing director Colin Hutchinson said the club had
received a fair hearing, but added that he was aggrieved by the
level of the fine. Nonetheless, he suggested that an appeal was
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
Last month the FA fined Leeds United and Tottenham Hotspur a
record 150,000 pounds each for a mass player brawl during a match
on the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
The FA said it had considered deducting points from both teams
for failing to control their players in their Premiership match at
Elland Road. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian government has given the green light for
energy firms to negotiate the sale of natural gas to Israel, after
it blocked such talks for years amid tension over the Middle East
peace process, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by the Egyptian Ministry of Petroleum during a
visit by Israeli Minister of National Infrastructure Eli Suissa
came after Israel discovered its own gas fields.
</P>
<P>
The two sides "agreed to encourage gas companies in the two
countries to enter trade negotiations," said a statement issued
after a meeting on Thursday between Sameh Fahmi, Egypt's minister
of petroleum, and Suissa. (Egypt-Israel-Gas Supply)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has informed the Arab League (AL) of the recent
bombings and airspace violations by the United States and Britain,
urging the pan-Arab forum to intervene to halt such aggressions,
the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to AL Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid,
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz elaborated the bombings and
violations by U.S. and British planes on April 2-9, when the U.S.
and British jets carried out 166 armed sorties from their bases in
Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Aziz condemned these aggressions, stressing that they represent
a continuation of a "hostile trend" by the U.S. and Britain against
Iraq. (Iraq-AL-Letter)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Friday issued the
most pessimistic review about peace talks with Syria since their
negotiations broke off in January.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference of his Labor party ministers in Tel
Aviv, Barak said he is "very pessimistic" regarding the
negotiations, though he believed a very narrow crack is still left
on the door for a possible resumption, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving on Monday for a summit with U.S President Bill
Clinton in Washington, Barak only said he was not optimistic about
chances of reviving the talks. (Israel-Syria-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin on Friday morning
visited the Zohar Agriculture Research Center, accompanied by his
Israeli counterpart Ezer Weizman.
</P>
<P>
The research center, located about 100 kilometers southeast of
Jerusalem, is one of Israel's advanced agriculture research and
experimental sites for fruits, vegetables, flowers and plants.
</P>
<P>
At the center, Jiang visited several greenhouses where fruits,
vegetables and flowers are grown, and asked many questions about
their specifications and cultivating process.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president talked with technicians and researchers
with great interest, and praised them for their achievements made
under harsh natural conditions. (Israel-China-Jiang)
</P>
