<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Recognize Palestinian State by May: Israeli TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel will recognize
Palestinian independence after the two sides reach a framework
agreement for final-status issues by the end of May, Israel Channel
One television reported Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Citing a senior source familiar with the negotiations, the
report said that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak had inclined to
agree to "the establishment of a demilitarized Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
No Israeli official could be reached for comment on the report
as most Israelis are observing the Jewish Sabbath during Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the television report, the border between Israel
and the future independent Palestinian state, however, will not be
decided finally in the framework peace agreement expected to be
drafted by the May deadline.
</P>
<P>
The borderline is reportedly expected to be demarcated between
them by September 13, when the two sides are due to seal a final
peace treaty under the Sharm el Sheikh memorandum they signed last
September.
</P>
<P>
Barak threw all his energy into the Israeli-Palestinian peace
track after he realized recently that chances to advance in the
peace talks with Syria, his favorite endeavor during his first 10
months in office, are really slim.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, he sent negotiators to meet with their
Palestinian counterparts in two rounds of talks at Bolling Air
Force in southeast Washington.
</P>
<P>
He also went to Washington in person to meet U.S. President Bill
Clinton earlier this week. It was believed that during the summit
Barak put forward the proposal to recognize a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The proposed recognition is also a good-will gesture to satisfy
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who toughened stance on declaring
Palestinian statehood on September 13, the seventh anniversary of
the birth of Oslo accords between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to travel to Washington and meet with
Clinton next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks, which were launched
last September, are aimed at resolving the most thorny issues
between the two sides, such as the status of Jerusalem, the return
of Palestinian refugees, water sharing, security arrangement and
the establishment of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The talks broke down in February due to differences over a long-
overdue transfer of another 6.1 percent land of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, which forced the two sides to miss the February 13
deadline for a framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
After intensive mediation by senior U.S. officials, Barak and
Arafat reached a compromise plan in March to delay the deadline for
a framework accord to mid-May.
</P>
<P>
It appears that after the temporary break, the two sides showed
most sincerity for peace in talks at the Bolling Air Base.
</P>
<P>
However, it is reported that Israel will not make any
concessions on the future of Jerusalem, the city which Israel
claimed as its "eternal and indivisible capital" and the
Palestinians want as the capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
According to the television report, Barak will not concede to
Palestinian demands on the question of the return of the 3.5
million Palestinian refugees either. 
</P>
</TEXT>
