<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Countries Criticize Bad Effect of Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
South countries have not been able to share in the benefits of
globalization on an equal footing with the developed countries and
have been essentially excluded from this process, said the final
document approve by 133 member countries in Cuba's capital city of
Havana in the first ever summit of the group in its history.
</P>
<P>
Asymmetries and imbalances have intensified in international
economic relations, particularly with regard to international
cooperation, widening even further the gap between the developing
countries and the industrialized countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
They are also concerned that within the widening North-South
gap, the social and economic conditions of the Least Developed
Counties (LDCs) have been deterioration. The income gap within
countries remain wide, social exclusion and inequalities are
widespread and the number of people living in poverty has
increased, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The Summit called to take urgent measures in order to address
the needs of the large majorities of the population, many of whom
live in villages, dependent on substance farming, otherwise,
golobalization will provide no solutions to the essential problems
of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the South also are concerned by the serious
financial problems faced by many of their countries.
</P>
<P>
The volatility of short-term financial flows and the absence of
an appropriate international regulatory framework, particularly in
light of the current volatility of financial markets are affecting
the developing countries, said the leaders in the document.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
