<HEADLINE> Europe's Major Markets Down on US Inflation Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 Index ended 178.9 points or 2.8 percent lower
on volume of 1.5 billion by the official close.
</P>
<P>
Tech shares knocked the London market back sharply. Baltimore
Technology slumped 25.8 percent, computer maker Psion slumped 14
percent, and software consultant Logica fell 7.7 percent and
computer systems integrator Sema Group dropped more than 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Index heavyweight Vodafone AirTouch weighed in with a 7 percent
loss, magazines and radio company EMAP slid 10 percent, and
Celltech, Britain's largest biotechnology company, fell more than
5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, "old economy" stocks held on to most of their early
gains. Britain's rail network operator Railtrack rose 2.3 percent,
while snacks and beverages producer Cadbury Schweppes rose 3.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's Xetra Dax fell 3.25 percent to 7207, with index
heavyweight Deutsche Telekom off 6.2 percent. The index fell more
than 4 percent this week.
</P>
<P>
Engineering and electronics conglomerate Siemens was down 5.8
percent, and electronic components maker Epcos fell 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 in Paris, heavily weighted with technology and media
stocks, tumbled 3.2 percent to 6065.73, off more than 4.1 percent
on the week. 
</P>
