<HEADLINE> U.S. Justice Department Asks Turnover of Cuban Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Justice Department spokeswoman Carole Florman said that the
government filed a brief this morning with the 11th Circuit Court
of Appeals in Atlanta, which had issued the temporary injunction
at the relatives' request on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government told the court that Elian's great-uncle Lazaro
Gonzalez, who has temporary custody, came to the court with "
unclean hands" and in violation of an order to surrender the boy,
Florman said.
</P>
<P>
The government said Lazaro should not get any help from the
court until he obeys the federal order, Florman said.
</P>
<P>
Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, agreed to stay in the
United States with the boy for that long if he has custody,
according to a letter from his attorney that was attached to the
government brief, Florman said.
</P>
<P>
"We are at a stage when Lazaro Gonzalez has failed to comply
with an INS order so we have now moved to implement an enforcement
action plan," said Maria Cardona, an INS spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
"I think it was the most appalling child manipulation and child
exploitation," Cardona said. "I thought it was shameful. If we
needed another reason to immediately move to reunite Elian with
his father, this was certainly it," she added.
</P>
<P>
The 11th Circuit Court of Appeals Thursday issued a temporary
stay that keeps the Cuban shipwreck survivor Elian in the United
States after the boy's Miami relatives defied a government
deadline to turn over the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 last year after his mother and
other 11 people died when their boat capsized in the Atlantic off
Florida. His relatives in Miami then took custody of him,
insisting that the boy should remain in the United States even
after the boy's father came to the U.S. to pick up his son.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department ruled earlier this year that the
boy belongs to his father and should be returned to Cuba. 
</P>
