<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Countries Rejects Unilateral Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Group of 77 (G-77)
member countries on Friday expressed their rejection to the
unilateral sanctions to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In the final documents -- Declaration of the South Summit
approved Friday after three-day meeting here in Cuban capital city
of Havana, they said they firmly reject the imposition of laws and
regulations with extraterritorial impact and all other forms of
coercive economic measures, including unilateral sanctions against
developing countries, urging the elimination of them.
</P>
<P>
Such actions not only undermine the principles of the Charter of
the United Nations and International Law, but also severely
threaten the freedom of trade and investment, said the document.
</P>
<P>
They call on the international community to neither recognize
these measures nor apply them.
</P>
<P>
They express grave concern over the impact of economic
sanctions on the civilian population and development capacity in
targeted countries and urge the international community to exhaust
all peaceful methods before resorting to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Libya has now fulfilled all its obligations in
terms of the pertinent Security Council Resolutions, so they urge
the Security Council to adopt a resolution completely lifting the
sanctions against Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
