<HEADLINE> UNICEF Director Concerned by Elian's Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 14 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) executive director Carol Bellamy Friday said that a
solution should be found as soon as possible to the case of Cuban
boy Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy told the press Friday at the Panamanian Foreign
Ministry that the case of the Cuban boy must be solved in favor of
the best interests of the child and that the way the case has been
handled so far directly affects Elian's rights.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF director arrived Thursday in this capital, at the
invitation of the Panamanian government for an official visit
related to the Tenth Iberoamerica Summit to be held November 17
and 18, of which the main theme will be childhood and youth.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy revealed that at the request of the United States and
the Cuban governments, "We are going to maintain our neutrality in
this case."
</P>
<P>
However, she said, at the request of the U.S. and the Cuban
governments, the UNICEF office in Havana, Cuba, has been serving
as a neutral territory for the dialogue in the case of the Cuban
boy.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban boy has been in the United States since he was
rescued on the sea in November of last year after a trip from Cuba
in which his mother drowned with other 10 Cubans.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the boy must be delivered to his
father, who now is in Washington, waiting to take his son back
with him to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
However, the relatives of the Cuban boy in the United States,
supported by U.S. politicians, ignored the U.S. government order
that the boy should be delivered to his father Thursday.  
</P>
