<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0359 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: South Leaders Call for Alleviation Debt Burdens  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Third World leaders called for the
alleviation, or even cancellation of foreign debts of the poorest
countries when they were speaking at the South Summit, the largest
gathering of heads of state or government of the Group of 77 since
its founding in 1964.
</P>
<P>
G-77 Chairman Olusegun Obasanjo, who is also the Nigerian
president, described the heavy debt burden as an obstacle to
economic and social development in developing countries, the
poorest ones in particular.
</P>
<P>
"This burden also discourages new foreign investments, so South
countries should be allowed to start looking for their socio-
economic progress over again," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rich countries must think on the possibility of immediately
eliminating the burden that foreign debt represents for the
poorest countries, taking into account the spirit of shared
responsibility in solving the vexing debt crisis.
</P>
<P>
South African President Thabo Mbeki, also chairman of the Non-
Aligned Movement (NAM), said that "the growing economic efforts of
our nations require a constructive and fruitful relation with the
North, focus on alleviating the burden that affects the South."
</P>
<P>
Mebki said that NAM defends common positions for the developing
world in favor of the long-dreamed permanent eradication of
poverty and improving the living standards of peoples in the
developing South.
</P>
<P>
What is in store for the South is the challenge of supporting
democratization of international institutions, including the
United Nations and the Bretton Woods institutions, namely the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cuban President Fidel Castro said, "Underdeveloped
countries' foreign debt is astonishing for its huge sum and
scandalous mechanism of exploitation and submission."
</P>
<P>
In fact, "the debt has already been paid, if we consider the
terms under which it was conceived, the rapid growth of dollar
interest rates and the decrease of prices in primary products," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The debt of poor people is a political, and not an economic
problem, which demands a political solution," he said. "We cannot
continue ignoring this problem should be mainly solved by those
who have the power and the means: the rich nations."
</P>
<P>
The Cuban leader reiterated that this phenomenon is one of the
greatest obstacles for development and a bomb ready to explode
under the world economy in any economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"As we has previously said, the Third World foreign debt is
unpayable and uncollectible," Castro said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who was also concerned over
the crushing debt burden, echoed the statement from South leaders,
and called on developed countries to allow the Third World
products a greater access to their markets, cancel the debts and
encouraged them to be more generous in helping development.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should be made to prevent developing nations from
continuing to face a great quantity of obstacles to their
participation in the global economy when they are confronted with
conflicts and epidemics, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debt was among topics under debates during the three-
day South Summit, which came as an opportunity to reflect on the
major problems facing developing countries and map out strategy
for social and economic development in the South.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
