<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Negotiators Exchange Papers of Each Views </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
delegations have exchanged papers outlining each sides' views for
a framework agreement, the U.S. State Department said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters that the
two delegations nearing the end of their talks at the Bolling Air
Force Base, southeast of Washington, had engaged in intensive,
serious and substantive discussions through the week.
</P>
<P>
"During the course of these discussions, the two sides
exchanged papers on this subject of how to create a skeleton for a
framework agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
The talks will wind up this weekend and negotiators on both
sides will return home for consultation with their leaders. Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the papers contained "all the core elements needed
for a framework agreement."
</P>
<P>
"Clearly there are tough issues and gaps that remain, but
obviously we want to continue working with the parties to overcome
those gaps," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hasan Abdel Rahman, the PLO's representative in Washington,
said it was an exchange of informal papers. "We presented the
Israelis with our understandings, and they presented us with
theirs," he said
</P>
<P>
"There is no progress on substance. There is a wide gap between
the two sides," Rahman added.
</P>
<P>
Mark Regev, the Israeli Embassy spokesman, said there had been
no expectation the current round of talks would produce historic
breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
"We are hoping for an energized process with the Palestinians,
and it can move if both sides show a seriousness and a level of
conciliation and a willingness to compromise," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that Washington agreed to "play a more intensive
role in the discussions and have greater involvement in the
discussions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
