<HEADLINE> American Vintners Association Supports China PNTR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) The American Vintners
Association (AVA), the national trade association representing 600
winery members in 43 states, urged Congress on Friday to approve
Permanent Normal Trade Relations (PNTR) with China before it gains
full membership in the World Trade Organization (WT0).
</P>
<P>
"China is recognized as a huge potential for American wineries,
but what is most interesting is the chance to enter this
tremendous market with a relatively level playing," AVA President
Simon Siegl said.
</P>
<P>
The American wine industry has the opportunity to benefit
greatly from the U.S.-China trade agreement signed last November,
under which tariffs on wine would be reduced from 65% to 20%
within three years of enactment and private companies would be
allowed to set up their own distribution system to secure much
greater market access.
</P>
<P>
AVA winery members are encouraged to make it clear to their
federal delegations that the passage of China PNTR is vitally
important to the development of new market, and a failure to do so
would hand the opportunity to their global competitors, the
Europeans in particular.
</P>
<P>
"In most third-market countries, American wineries are
constantly attempting to overcome the domination of major
producers of the European Union. This agreement with China places
everyone at the same starting position," Siegl said.
</P>
<P>
AVA is a member of the Agricultural Coalition for U.S.-China
Trade, which includes 75 associations representing agricultural
interests in Washington DC. The Coalition is an effective vehicle
in channeling the American farmers' message for PNTR to the
Capitol Hill, where the vote will be cast on the issue in the week
of May 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
