<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup--Common Wishes and Fair Demands by the South  (by Xue Hong, Sun Guangying) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wishes and claims by South countries consist in establishing a
new international economic order, intensifying South-South
cooperation, deepening dialogue and relations with the North,
building a true free trade system, and access to advanced
technology.
</P>
<P>
It is meaningful that South countries could have built a
consensus on the path to follow, a prevision looking into the
future, a wide strategy and common goals in the future.
</P>
<P>
This constitutes a concrete collective actions platform with
the purpose of defending developing countries interests, in the
face of the fact that many of these are in the margins of
globalization, with a widening North-South gap.
</P>
<P>
Amidst intensified globalization, the definition of economic
and trade rules at a world level has a special meaning, since they
have been set up by countries of the North, and are for their own
benefit.
</P>
<P>
South countries believe that they have to be aware with
globalization, development, in the center of economic and
technical world revolution, to the articulation of their concerns
and opinions, to the elaboration of the rules of the game.
</P>
<P>
Southern countries wish to participate in the benefits of
globalization in equal conditions with countries of the North, and
the declaration makes a call to carry out a common action of the
South in the face of world globalization, an integral position
before a reform of the international monetary and financial system,
to influence in the development of economic policies and in search
of effective and fast solutions for the problems affecting the
South.
</P>
<P>
In these documents approved by the heads of state and the
representatives of the 122 participating countries, South
countries claim to safeguard sovereignty, equality of national
interests in the face of globalization's opportunities and
challenges. Representatives of the South countries coincide in
considering that it is important to avoid becoming appendixes of
the North.
</P>
<P>
The growing weight of foreign investments and the role of
transnationals, generally from the North, in the economies of the
countries from the South threaten their sovereignty and
independence, because their governments are loosing their power to
undertake a macroeconomic adjust in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Capitals are freely flowing, generally from North countries, as
financial or productive system investments, generally in the South,
they have to do with the
financial and economic system of these countries.
</P>
<P>
It is not an easy thing for the South countries to receive
help from the nations of the North, for this help is always
conditioned with "improving human rights, driving democracy, and
applying austerity and reform policies."
</P>
<P>
The austerity conditions of the assistance, considered by
important characters from the South as "many thunders, and little
water," do not precisely make benefits to stay.
</P>
<P>
South is demanding to erase the incredible inequality between
countries of the South and the North, foreign debt condonation,
access to markets and to advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
The gap between North and South is widening. About 86 percent
of the world's gross domestic product is controlled by a reduced
part of the countries of the North. Productive factors of utmost
importance are dominated and controlled by the North. Resources
and income go easily to North countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there exist alarming problems in the South, such as
intense richness concentration, extreme inequality, burdensome
foreign debt, famines, diseases and illiteracy, among others,
beyond any achievement done.
</P>
<P>
The Summit considers important to drive North-South dialogue,
because the South cannot handle its matters without the North in a
world in which interdependency is growing, and the gap between
both sectors of the world is widening.
</P>
<P>
In the Summit, the South countries demand the universalization
of the World Trade Organization (WTO), the elimination of
unbalances between rights and obligations, the removal of trade
barriers and other unfair trade practices, as well as many other
protectionism forms, in spite South countries are not against
liberalization of world trade, but against those measures.
</P>
<P>
Poor countries make up a great market, which covers three
quarters of the planet, but only control 10 percent of world trade,
because the most part of trade is carried out among rich nations.
</P>
<P>
Due to globalization and the fast development of science and
technology, traditional products, mainly from the South, give up
more space to manufactured, modern technology, mainly from the
North.
</P>
<P>
Besides non-tariff barriers, such as sanitary, technical and
subsidiary, imposed by countries of the North, prevent the
establishment of a real free trade between North and South,
affecting basically underdeveloped countries.
</P>
<P>
South countries made a call for the establishment of a common
South strategy in the World Trade Organization (WTO) to negotiate.
They wish the interests of developing countries be taken into
account when a new round of negotiations takes place.
</P>
<P>
They claim to abstain of establishing excessive or onerous
exigencies to developing countries, in considering that the
creation of a free trade must include everyone.
</P>
<P>
South countries are aware of their unity to become a true
multinational force. That is their main challenge.
</P>
<P>
The integration of South countries is still the best way of
cooperation in their search for development and growth, inputting
courage and strength to face current challenges.
</P>
<P>
Thus South countries seek to promote the formation of a debtors
club, constituting a banking institution of the South, to create a
telecommunications company and to create an electronic network of
commerce chambers of the South, among others.
</P>
<P>
Besides, South countries are decided to improve the G-77, for
they consider it a political, economic and commercial alliance
with great influence in developing member countries, a mechanism
of negotiation in a unified position to raise its negotiating
capability.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0365 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
