<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS, Another Burden for the Third World: G-77 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Third World must bear,
together with the inequalities in the commercial exchange and the
foreign debt burden, the highest figure of cases of Acquired
Immuno-Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS), an epidemic that decimates in
the first place all the inhabitants and resources of the
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of the pandemics among the developing countries,
especially in Africa, emerged Friday in the interventions of the
delegates to the Southern Summit in the Cuban capital, where many
have expressed the social pressure into which that disease
translates itself.
</P>
<P>
Justin Malewezi, Malawi Republic (Africa) Vice President, was
one of the leaders in the Southern Summit who insisted the most on
the theme on Friday, by remembering that some 23 million of the 36
million of carriers of the Human Immuno-defficiency Virus (HIV)
live in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He made a very concrete proposal by saying that the millions of
money the debtor countries direct to the service of their foreign
commitments, should be channeled to the fight against the terrible
disease.
</P>
<P>
Data quoted Friday during the meeting of the Group of 77 show
that 2.6 million persons died in 1999 victims of AIDS, which still
roams uncontrolled in the poor world, inhabited by 95 percent of
the sero-positive population.
</P>
<P>
United Nations General -Secretary Kofi Annan called at the
start of the meeting in this capital to approve in an explicit way
the target of reducing the rate of infection in young people
during the Summit of the Millennium, scheduled for September in
New York.
</P>
<P>
AIDS, said Annan, threatens with annulling a whole generation
of human development.
</P>
<P>
The Final Declaration of the Summit, to be approved Friday by
the heads of state and of government, asks for the adoption of
strategies that will help prevent AIDS from continuing being a
menace for the Third World.
</P>
<P>
Cuba announced also today, in relation to the theme, that it
will start to produce in the next months medicines to combat the
disease, from which the nations of the South can benefit, because
the high prices of such preparations when they are imported from
the industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
The Caribbean country also continues investigating to produce
an AIDS vaccine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
