<HEADLINE> Bush's Fund-raising Breaks New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican presumptive
presidential nominee George W. Bush has raised more than 81
million dollars in his campaign, setting a new record in U.S.
history.
</P>
<P>
The campaign raised around 7 million dollars between March 1
and April 6, three-quarters of the goal of 10 million dollars by
the end of April, campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the campaign also raised 1.6 million dollars
online by March 31 after it stepped up online fund raising.
</P>
<P>
Since the presidential primary season started in January, the
Texas Governor spent 63.3 million dollars of the record 71 million
dollars raised, leaving about 7.5 million dollars in the bank.
</P>
<P>
The de facto Democratic presidential nominee, Vice President Al
Gore, had around 10 million dollars to spend as of the end of
February.
</P>
<P>
Both Bush and Gore are expected to report their fund-raising
figures to the Federal Election Commission on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gore can spend no more than 40.5 million dollars as he is
receiving federal funds during the primary period while Bush does
not have such a limit.
</P>
<P>
Both Bush and Gore will collect 67.6 million dollars each in
federal money after their presidential nominations are confirmed
at their parties' national conventions this summer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
