<HEADLINE> G-77 Concerned over Assistance Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We exhort developed countries to comply with their compromise
of destining 0.7 percent of their gross domestic product for this
kind of assistance," said the Summit's Declaration approved on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 South Summit took place from April 12 to 14 with the
participation of heads of state from member countries at Havana,
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The block demanded the reduction or cancellation of foreign
debts not be carried out at the expense of official assistance for
development.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 called for convening of an International Conference on
Development Financing to define a new strategical frame of
cooperation and a new global association to provide resources for
growth.
</P>
<P>
The vicious circle between debt and underdevelopment has
worsened, said the document.
</P>
<P>
"We are alarmed because the debt service has grown at a higher
rate than the debt itself," that is, it is worse in those South
countries with low or medium income, says the document.
</P>
<P>
The block said that the debt service has worsened in many South
countries, including those with medium and low income.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 showed its particular concern for Africa, where it
said the debt growth, official assistance for development, and the
fall of its product's prices worsen economic and social conditions
in the countries of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
