<HEADLINE> South Leaders Slam Negative Impact of Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Iranian Vice President Hassan Habibi Friday called for more
logic, balanced and equal ties in the World, something the
countries in the South could achieve by implementing the
appropriate mechanisms after the Summit, which opened here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is hard to explain, he said, the sad irony of World history
in the last three centuries, during which a group of countries
from the North have plundered those in the South, depriving them
of self-determination, and keeping them subject to economic
backwardness.
</P>
<P>
James Michel, vice president of the Republic of Seychelles said
that the foreign debt continues to be the main factor that stunts
economic growth among developing countries, fed by the steady
decline in prices of basic products.
</P>
<P>
In that regard, he proposed that the Summit approve a package
of measures to relief the debt burden, also providing for the
frame to release the necessary resources that would help finance
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
But sustainable development needs a peaceful environment to
take place, said vice president of Malawi in a separate speech,
adding that poverty, illiteracy and communicable diseases continue
to be untackled problems for the Third World.
</P>
<P>
Frank Watson, vice prime minister of Bahamas, who spoke on
behalf of those many small island nations that are twice as
vulnerable to the current trends of economic liberalization, also
demanded that their voice to be heard at the decision-taking
circles in the North.
</P>
<P>
For the vice primer Minister of Uganda, Eriya Kategaya, the
fast path of globalization has brought no prosperity at all, but
turned instead into a two-edged knife that yielded higher
standards of living for a few, while leaving the majority in the
shadows of poverty.
</P>
<P>
The Summit came as many developing countries are being
marginalized in the tide of globalization due to the present
injust and unfair international political and economic system.
</P>
</TEXT>
