<HEADLINE> South Summit Asks Israel to Leave Occupied Territories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- South Summit of the Group of 77 (
G-77) demanded Friday Israel to withdraw From all the Arab
territories occupied in the Middle East to promote the peace and
the economic and social development of the region.
</P>
<P>
"We reaffirm our support to the Middle East peace process on
the basis of the UN Security Council resolutions 242 (1967), 338 (
1973), and 425 (1978)," said leaders of the G-77 in their
declaration published Friday.
</P>
<P>
Numerous chiefs of state of the Group of 77 countries took part
in the summit held April 12-14 in Havana, where a meeting between
Cuban President Fidel Castro and Palestine head of state Yasser
Arafat was held.
</P>
<P>
The leaders expressed their support to the principle of "land
for peace" and demanded the Israeli withdrawal from territories
occupied in Palestine, including Jerusalem, Sirya and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We affirm that to end the Israeli occupation and achieve an
integral, just, and lasting peace in the Middle East is a
requisite for the economic and social development of the region,"
said the bloc in the text of its declaration.
</P>
<P>
"The peace demands the total Israeli withdrawal from the
occupied Palestine territory, including Jerusalem, and the
achievement of a final agreement in the agreed-on date, September
of 2000, as well as the establishment of the Palestine State with
Jerusalem as its capital," added the Group of 77 declaration.
</P>
<P>
The leaders demanded the withdrawal of Israel from the Golan
Heights, in Sirya, and from the south of Lebanon, "to the
internationally recognized borders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
