<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges 617 Points on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks plunged
Friday in fears of inflation after a report on an unexpectedly
strong rise in consumer prices in March.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 617.78 or 5.6
percent at 10,305.77, extending its loss of 201.58 points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators also fell sharply. The technology
heavy Nasdaq composite index dropped 355.49 or 9.7 percent at 3,
321.29 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 83.95 or 5.8
percent at 1,356.56.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq index has dropped 1,727 points or 34 percent from
its record closing high of 5,048.62 points set on March 10,
falling deeply into bear-market territory. A drop of 20 percent or
more was defined as bear market.
</P>
<P>
The market tumbled as the Labor Department reported that
consumer inflation rose 0.7 percent in March, worse than 0.5
percent analysts have expected. The report added to new fears in
inflation, which were triggered Thursday by another report on a
wholesale prices increase in the same month.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times as a
pre-emptive move to keep inflation under control and the plunge in
technology stock recently dose not seem to change the Federal
Reserve's plan for more rise in rates. The Federal Reserve
chairman Alan Greenspan indicated at a congressional hearing
Thursday that the recent plummet in the technology stocks would do
little to deter his plan to raise rates again.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 33.12 at 611.49 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 57.26 at 857.97. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 35.52 at 453.72.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by 6-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 2,672 down, 434 up and 339 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased 1.25 billion shares from 1.03 billion in
the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
