<DOCNO> XIE20000414.0373 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: South Leaders Call for Fair Play in Globalization (by Gu Zhenqiu)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at the historic event, which kicked off on Wednesday,
leaders from Algeria, Malaysia, Barbados, Pakistan and Palestine
criticized the negative effects of globalization on economic and
social development, trade, and access to sophisticated science and
technology in the South.
</P>
<P>
Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflik, currently chairman of
the Organization of African Unity, said that the South's non-
participation in decision-making in international economic
relations has created inequality in globalization.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries are being marginalized in the tide of
globalization, which resulted from the advancement of science and
technology, including information technology.
</P>
<P>
An example of such marginalization is the amount of foreign
investments considered derisive, especially in African countries,
due to the heavy debt burden in the South, he said. "The vicious
circle must be broken."
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the marginalization on unfair trade in the
world,where raw materials from the South are constantly devalued
in the world markets controlled by the North.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said
that globalization should contribute to a more fair and equitable
world economic order.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the process today turned out to be a synonym
for inequality, he said. "Globalization threatens to become a
religion that doesn't permit heresy."
</P>
<P>
The South Summit, which is to end here on Friday night, came
in the largest gathering of heads of state and government of the
Group of 77 (G-77) since its founding in 1964.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Pakistan encouraged G-77 members to support
the nation's call to an international conference on globalization
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani chief executive, Pervez Musharraf, held that the
resources used to buy weapons for regional wars and conflicts
should be dedicated to health and education program in those
countries.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, he underlined the importance of the South-South
cooperation, saying that South countries should cooperate in this
unfair world.
</P>
<P>
Representing the Caribbean, Owen Arthur, prime minister of
Barbados, stressed the need for more participation in
international
financial decision-making by the South.
</P>
<P>
Palestine leader Yasser Arafat agreed that globalization is a
powerful and dynamic force to empower cooperation and accelerate
development that presents opportunities and risks at the same time.
</P>
<P>
In their separate speeches, many South leaders sang in one
voice,calling for the establishment of a fair, rational new
international political and economic order to safeguard the
collective interests of developing countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
